(5.1 cm)", "credit_line": "Purchase, Gift of Mrs. Russell Sage, by exchange, 1958", "description": "This set of four tumblers or small drinking cups (58.3.1-.4) was made for the Salem, Massachusetts merchant Elias Hasket Derby (1739\\u20131799) and descended in his family. They are among the \"12 Silver tumblers\" that Revere supplied to Derby in 1797. Their plain, slightly rounded bodies with engraved borders were made to match a set of four cups already owned by Derby, marked by the Parisian silversmith Denis Colombier in 1789. The similarities are striking, although the French originals are more intricately engraved. These objects illustrate both the influence of French design on late eighteenth-century American taste and the role of the patron in commissioning silver. One of the Colombier beakers (67.94) also belongs to the Museum, offering the opportunity to compare copies to their original source.", "classification": "Silver", "accession_number": "58.3.4", "geographic_location": "Boston,Massachusetts,North and Central America,United States", "artist_maker_culture": "Paul Revere Jr.", "object_type_material": "Drinking glasses,Drinking vessels,Metal,Silver,Tumblers"}

column23: {"date": "1870", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ap/web-large/ap09.176.jpg", "title": "The Muse of Painting", "artist": "John La Farge (American, New York 1835\\u20131910 Providence, Rhode Island)", "medium": "Oil on canvas", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/11379", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1800\\u20131900", "dimensions": "49 1/2 x 38 1/4 in. (125.7 x 97.2 cm)", "credit_line": "Gift of J. Pierpont Morgan and Henry Walters, 1909", "description": "By 1870, La Farge had moved away from his early realistic manner to a more decorative, academic style of easel painting. \"The Muse of Painting\" synthesizes the different and somewhat contradictory tendencies found in his work at this time. The landscape represents a site that artist painted frequently, the ridge behind Bishop Berkeley's Rock near his farm outside of Newport, Rhode Island. The figure belongs to the mainstream of nineteenth-century ideal painting, representing an allegory of the art of painting. In an odd twist, La Farge depicted the muse as an artist rather than as the inspiratrice of an artist. Her inspiration is the surrounding landscape of Newport, proving that nature is the true muse of painting. The landscape and overall composition are handled in highly decorative manner, mingling carefully observed details with dreamy, evocative colors.", "classification": "Paintings", "accession_number": "09.176", "geographic_location": "North and Central America,United States", "artist_maker_culture": "John La Farge", "object_type_material": "Canvas,Oil paintings,Paintings"}

{"date": "ca. 1796", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ap/web-large/DT11608.jpg", "title": "Albert Gallatin", "artist": "James Sharples (ca. 1751\\u20131811)", "medium": "Pastel on light gray wove paper", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/12558", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1600\\u20131800", "dimensions": "9 3/8 x 7 3/8 in. (23.8 x 18.7 cm)", "credit_line": "Gift of Miss Josephine L. Stevens, 1908", "description": "The popularity of profile portraits, which ultimately derived from classical medallions honoring famous men of the republics of Greece and Rome, burgeoned during America\\u2019s Federal period. The English painter and pastelist James Sharples established a career in America in 1794 by asking local and national politicians to sit for profiles and then enticing them into commissioning one or more copies of the completed portraits. Perhaps with some exceptions, Sharples employed a physiognotrace to record an exact profile and then retained the original portrait for his personal collection, a library of images that he could copy for sale over and over again. Sharples\\u2019s profile of the diplomat Albert Gallatin is perhaps the earliest likeness of a man who would be portrayed many times during the course of his long and prestigious career; when he sat for Sharples in about 1796, Gallatin was a member of the U.S. House of Representatives, where he remained for three terms.", "classification": "Drawings", "accession_number": "08.144", "geographic_location": "England,Europe,United Kingdom", "artist_maker_culture": "James Sharples", "object_type_material": "Drawings,Paper,Pastels,Wove paper"}

column23: {"date": "1883\\u20131900", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ad/web-large/DT11617.jpg", "maker": "Associated Artists (1883\\u20131907)", "title": "Sample", "medium": "Printed and woven cotton velvet", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/14008", "culture": "American", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "designer": "Candace Wheeler (American, Delhi, New York 1827\\u20131923 New York)", "geography": "Made in New York, New York, United States", "dimensions": "32 1/2 x 37 in. (82.6 x 94 cm)", "credit_line": "Gift of Mrs. Boudinot Keith, 1928", "description": "Candace Wheeler (1827-1933), who probably designed his fabric, was a partner in Tiffany\\u2019s short-lived interior decorating firm \\u201cLouis C. Tiffany & Company, Associated Artists\\u201d (1881-83) along with painter Samuel Colman and designer Lockwood de Forest. When the firm dissolved and Wheeler went on to create her own textile design company, she continued to use the \\u201cAssociated Artists\\u201d name. The use of a pile fabric as the ground for a printed pattern \\u2013 in this case, cotton velvet \\u2013 was relatively innovative at the time. The three-dimensional texture and light reflected from the surface of the pile contribute to the overall decorative effect of the design. The pattern of daffodils, with sinuous curving stems and leaves, is one of the firm\\u2019s designs closest in spirit to the Art Nouveau style. A sense of movement pervades the boldly drawn, naturalistic blossoms twisting and turning in all directions as they might on a windy spring day.", "classification": "Textiles", "accession_number": "28.70.25", "geographic_location": "New York,New York City,North and Central America,United States", "artist_maker_culture": "Associated Artists,Candace Wheeler", "object_type_material": "Cotton,Printing,Samples,Textiles,Velvet,Woven"}

General Eliott commanded the British garrison against the allied Spanish and French forces at Gibraltar (1779\\u201383). column23: {"date": "ca. 1580", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/aa/web-large/sfma29.154.1_156870.jpg", "title": "Armor for the Tilt", "medium": "Steel, brass, leather", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/23203", "armorer": "Attributed to Anton Peffenhauser (German, Augsburg, 1525\\u20131603)", "culture": "German, Augsburg", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "geography": "Augsburg", "dimensions": "H. 68 3/4 in. (174.6 cm); W. at shoulders 18 in. (45.72 cm); Wt. 81 lb. (36.8 kg)", "credit_line": "Bashford Dean Memorial Collection, Gift of Helen Fahnestock Hubbard, in memory of her father, Harris C. Fahnestock, 1929", "description": "This armor has an elegant sculptural quality that is characteristic of the finest Augsburg armors. It is identical in appearance to a series of tournament armors ordered by the duke of Bavaria in 1579\\u201380 from Anton Peffenhauser, the leading armorer in Augsburg during the second half of the sixteenth century. In the joust, or tilt, in the German fashion, two contestants armed with blunt lances rode at one another, left side to left side, separated by a barrier (called a tilt), the object being to break lances or unseat the opponent. Because the left side of the rider was thus particularly vulnerable, it was given additional protection in the form of large, smooth reinforcing plates that would deflect the blow of the lance. Characteristic of these armors are the helm screwed to the breastplate and backplate, the tilt targe (the cape-like defense for the left shoulder) screwed directly to the breastplate, a passguard (the reinforcing plate over the left elbow), and the manifer (overized left gauntlet).", "classification": "Armor for Man", "accession_number": "29.154.1a\\u2013u", "geographic_location": "Augsburg,Bavaria,Europe,Germany", "artist_maker_culture": "Anton Peffenhauser", "object_type_material": "Armor,Armors,Brass,Copper alloy,Costume,Iron alloy,Iron and iron alloy,Leather,Metal,Steel,Tilt armors,Tournament armors"}

column19: Morion for the Bodyguard of the Prince-Elector of Saxony
column23: {"date": "ca. 1600", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/aa/web-large/04.3.225_011june2015.jpg", "title": "Morion for the Bodyguard of the Prince-Elector of Saxony", "medium": "Steel, gold, brass, leather, textile", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/25387", "culture": "German, probably Nuremberg", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "geography": "probably Nuremberg", "dimensions": "H. 16 1/4 in. (41.3 cm); W. 14 7/8 in. (37.8 cm); D. 14 11/16 in. (37.3 cm); Wt. 4 lb. 8.6 oz. (2058.2 g)", "credit_line": "Rogers Fund, 1904", "description": "The electors of Saxony appear to have been the only German princes in the sixteenth century to outfit their bodyguards with matching equipment. The guards' helmets are etched and gilt on one side with the coat of arms of the dukedom of Saxony and on the other side with the crossed swords that signify the duke's office as archmarshal of the Holy Roman Empire. The gilt decoration was originally contrasted with black painted surfaces (some now polished bright). The black and gold derived from the Saxon coat of arms and were also the colors of the guards' livery. This helmet was made by armorers in Nuremberg. Another example (1989.288) in the Metropolitan Museum's collection is dated 1568. The only dated morion of this series known, it establishes the creation and use of the guard morions in the reign of August I (1553\\u201386), twenty to thirty years earlier than previously thought.", "classification": "Helmets", "accession_number": "04.3.225", "geographic_location": "Bavaria,Europe,Germany,Nuremberg", "object_type_material": "Armor,Body armor,Brass,Copper alloy,Costume,Gold,Helmets,Iron alloy,Iron and iron alloy,Leather,Metal,Morions,Steel,Textiles"}

column17: Eastern Tibetan or Chinese for the Tibetan market
column23: {"date": "17th\\u201318th century", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/aa/web-large/DP113274.jpg", "title": "Saddle (gser sga)", "medium": "Iron, gold, silver, wood, leather, textile", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/26656", "culture": "Eastern Tibetan or Chinese for the Tibetan market", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "dimensions": "H. 10 3/4 in. Grancsay, by exchange, 1997", "description": "This saddle represents a particular form found in Tibet, one that is Chinese or strongly influenced by Chinese types. It belongs to a small group of closely related saddles that may stem from a single workshop or reflect a specific type developed in one region. Notable features are the lively dragons, chiseled free from the scrollwork ground, and the unusual decorative technique involving silver damascening of the entire surfaces of the saddle plates, with select design elements highlighted by mercury gilding over the silver. Also very distinctive is the use of three layers of decoration: the outer layer of pierced scrollwork with long tendrils deeply undercut to give an appearance of depth, a second layer forming a subsidiary ground underlying each saddle plate and consisting of an iron grill damascened in silver to create a stylized cloud pattern, and a layer of colored cloth directly on top of the wood of the saddle-tree.", "classification": "Equestrian Equipment-Saddles", "accession_number": "1997.214.1", "geographic_location": "Asia,China,Tibet", "object_type_material": "Gold,Iron,Iron and iron alloy,Leather,Metal,Saddles,Silver,Textiles"}

column19: Portrait of Jnanatapa Attended by Lamas and Mahasiddhas
column23: {"date": "ca. 1350", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/as/web-large/DP318742.jpg", "title": "Portrait of Jnanatapa Attended by Lamas and Mahasiddhas", "medium": "Distemper on cloth", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/37801", "culture": "Eastern Tibet, Kham, Riwoche monastery", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1000\\u20131400", "dimensions": "27 x 21 1/2 in. (68.6 x 54.6 cm)", "credit_line": "Purchase, Friends of Asian Art Gifts, 1987", "description": "This portrait was created for Riwoche monastery in eastern Tibet, a branch of Taklung monastery. The central figure and the assembled abbots are not directly named on the painting. Nonetheless, two inscriptions allow a lineage identification: the epithet Jnanatapa (\\u201cheat of wisdom\\u201d) appears on the painting\\u2019s veil, a name denoting a famous Indian mahasiddha, the spiritual fathers of Tantric Buddhism. The second is the identity of presiding deity above the central figure, named as Avagarbha. The importance of these two clues is revealed by their presence in the official history of Taklung monastery, which tells that the first abbot of Riwoche monastery was an incarnation of \\u201cthe peerless mahasiddha Jnanatapa\\u201d and that his Tantric teacher was Avagarbha, a Bengal  siddha. Hence, this portrait is intended to invoke the spiritual lineage of Taklung and Riwoche monasteries through the person of mahasiddha Jnanatapa.", "classification": "Paintings", "accession_number": "1987.144", "geographic_location": "Asia,China,Tibet", "object_type_material": "Cloth,Distemper,Paintings"}

column23: {"date": "ca. 1095", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/as/web-large/DP153769.jpg", "title": null, "artist": "Huang Tingjian (Chinese, 1045–1105)", "medium": "Handscroll; ink on paper", "period": "Northern Song dynasty (960–1127)", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/39918", "culture": "China", "cc_domain": "creativecommons.org", "Date / Era": "A.D. 1000–1400", "cc_license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "dimensions": "Image: 13 1/4 in. × 60 ft. 4 1/2 in. Crawford Jr., 1988", "description": "Poet, calligrapher, and Chan (Zen) Buddhist adept, Huang Tingjian believed that calligraphy should be spontaneous and self-expressive—“a picture of the mind.” Containing nearly twelve hundred characters, this handscroll is a master­piece of cursive-script writing. It transcribes an account of a rivalry between two officials: Lian Po, a distinguished general; and Lin Xiangru, a skilled strategist. Huang’s transcription ends abruptly with Lin’s words: “When two tigers fight, one must perish. I behave as I do because I put our country’s fate before private feuds.” Read in the context of Song political infighting, Huang’s transcription becomes a powerful indictment of the partisanship that led to his own banishment in 1094.", "classification": "Calligraphy", "accession_number": "1989.363.4", "Geographic Location": "Asia,China", "Object Type / Material": "Calligraphy,Handscrolls,Ink,Paintings,Paper,Scroll paintings", "Artist / Maker / Culture": "Huang Tingjian"}

column19: Birds and Flowers of the Twelve Months with Chinese Calligraphy
column23: {"date": "16th century; sheets of poetry, one dated 1553", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/as/web-large/DT1611.jpg", "title": null, "artist": "Kano School", "medium": "Pair of six-panel folding screens; ink and color and gold leaf on paper", "period": "Muromachi period (1392–1573)", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/45639", "culture": "Japan", "cc_domain": "creativecommons.org", "Date / Era": "A.D. 1400–1600", "cc_license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "dimensions": "Image (each screen): 60 11/16 x 139 1/8 in. (154.1 x 353.4 cm)", "credit_line": "Gift of Mrs. P. H. B. Frelinghuysen, 1962", "description": "Although traditionally it was common to paint entire scenes directly onto folding screens, alternatively, an allover design could be painted on the panels, to which small fans or albums of painting or calligraphy would then be attached. This set of screens is unusual in that the background design was painted on the screen with the knowledge that large paintings would be placed on top; that is, the screens were custom-made to accommodate these skillful bird-and-flower paintings, no doubt created by a Kano atelier artist of the late sixteenth century. Each panel of this pair of screens contains both a painted scene in a fan-shaped cartouche and a sheet of calligraphy that has been cut in half to replicate the squarish proportions of Japanese shikishi (square poem cards). The twelve scenes of birds and flowers present a progression of the characteristic flora and fauna of the four seasons. The sheets of poetry contain verses on the theme of plums in winter, which were composed and inscribed by six Chinese scholars, including Huang Yuanxu, who dated his piece to autumn 1553.", "classification": "Screens", "accession_number": "62.98.2, .3", "Geographic Location": "Asia,Japan", "Object Type / Material": "Furniture,Gold,Gold leaf,Ink,Metal,Panels,Paper,Screens", "Artist / Maker / Culture": "Kano School"}

column19: Rank Badge with a Pair of Cranes
column23: {"date": "late 19th century", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/as/web-large/DP109338.jpg", "title": "Rank Badge with a Pair of Cranes", "medium": "Silk embroidery on silk satin damask", "period": "Joseon dynasty (1392\\u20131910)", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/49599", "culture": "Korea", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1800\\u20131900", "dimensions": "Overall: 8 1/4 x 7 1/2 in. (21 x 19.1 cm)", "credit_line": "Seymour Fund, 1953", "description": "In 1454, the court of the Joseon dynasty (1392\\u20131910) adopted a system of insignia of rank for civil and military officials based on that of China's Ming dynasty (1368\\u20131644). Square badges of embroidered birds and animals on silk were worn on the front (hyung) and back (bae) of official costumes. They are clearly differentiated from the round badges embroidered with a dragon (called bo) worn by the king and the crown prince on the front, back, and shoulders of their court attire. Besides being ornamental, rank badges served as visible status markers in a society that prized strict social and political hierarchy. Initially permitted for wear by civil and military officials of the third rank and higher, eventually the use of rank badges was broadened to all nine ranks. Regulations on the specific animal imagery and correlating ranks evolved over the course of the Joseon dynasty. Rank badges with a pair of cranes were usually reserved for civil officials of the first to third rank. The system of hyungbae was suspended in 1899.", "classification": "Textiles-Embroidered", "accession_number": "53.60.9", "geographic_location": "Asia,Korea", "object_type_material": "Badges,Damask,Embroidery,Needlework,Satin,Silk,Textiles"}

Bell Funds, Joseph Pulitzer Bequest, and The Annenberg Fund Inc. Gift, 1975", "description": "Among all Noh masks, the Okina (old man) mask is considered particularly sacred and has been at times treated as the embodiment of god, bringing longevity and prosperity to families. This sacred mask is discreetly shown here peering from a mask bag that is richly embellished with the auspicious motifs of a tortoise-shell pattern and a circular crane design. Zeshin has used lacquer painting with inlays of mother-of-pearl and gold fragments. The painting would have been displayed on auspicious occasions to express celebratory wishes for longevity. The ivory roller ends have been decorated in lacquer by Ikeda Taishin (1825\\u20131903), Zeshin's student.", "classification": "Paintings", "accession_number": "1975.268.136", "geographic_location": "Asia,Japan", "artist_maker_culture": "Shibata Zeshin", "object_type_material": "Gold,Hanging scrolls,Ink,Lacquer,Metal,Mother of pearl,Paintings,Paper,Scroll paintings,Scrolls"}

Gift, 1975", "description": "This miniature wooden pagoda (tŏ) is one of one million (hyakuman) commissioned by the Empress Shŏtoku (718–770) and distributed to Japan’s ten major temples. It originally was created to commemorate and offer thanks to Buddhist deities for their help in suppressing the Emi Rebellion in 764. This example belonged to the temple Hŏryǔji in Nara, where three thousand of the one million pagodas were given away in 1908 to those contributing to an appeal for funds. Each pagoda was painted white and contained a printed Buddhist text called a darani (Sanskrit: dharani), or invocation. The text displayed here came from the pagoda on known as the Jishin’in darani, the invocation is one of four from the sacred text Mukujŏkŏkyŏ (Sanskrit: Vimala Mirbhasa Sutra) found in the pagodas. These printed texts are among the oldest known in the world. They are likely to have been printed from bronze plates, but some scholars maintain that they were printed from woodblocks.", "classification": "Sculpture", "accession_number": "1975.268.150a, b", "Geographic Location": "Asia,Japan", "Object Type / Material": "Cypress,Sculpture,Softwood,Wood"}

{"date": "ca. 1805", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ci/web-large/26.495_front_CP4.jpg", "title": "Dress", "medium": "silk", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/157126", "culture": "American", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1800\\u20131900", "credit_line": "Brooklyn Museum Costume Collection at The Metropolitan Museum of Art, Gift of the Brooklyn Museum, 2009; Gift of Charles Blaney, 1926", "description": "The Empire silhouette is readily identified with its origins in the chiton of ancient Greco-Romans, which was a tubular garment draped from the shoulders and sometimes belted beneath the bust.  Several re-interpretations have occurred throughout costume history but none have been as notable as the period bridging the rectangular panierred skirts of the 18th century and the conical hoop skirts of the 19th century.  The neoclassic style was adopted in all forms of decoration after the French Revolution and was upheld during the Napoleonic Wars partly due to Napoleon Bonaparte's (1769-1821) alliance with Greco-Roman principles.  In fashion, the style began as children's wear made from fine white cotton, but was adopted by women in the form of a tubular dress with skirts that were gathered under the bust with some fullness over a pad at the back.  As the style progressed the skirts began to flatten at the front and solely gather from the bodice at the center back.  The style persisted until the 1820s when the waist slowly lowered and the skirts became more bell shaped.", "accession_number": "2009.300.2314", "geographic_location": "North and Central America,United States", "object_type_material": "Costume,Dresses,Silk"}

{"date": "1767\\u201368", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/es/web-large/39731.jpg", "title": "Snuffbox", "medium": "Gold, enamel, heliotrope, ivory, glass", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/193884", "culture": "French, Paris", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1600\\u20131800", "dimensions": "H. 1 15/16 in. (4.9cm); Diam: 3 in. (7.6cm)", "credit_line": "Gift of J. Pierpont Morgan, 1917", "description": "In eighteenth-century Europe, Paris led the production of high-quality luxury goods. Parisian goldsmiths made a wide range of small, personal articles such as snuffboxes; \\xe9tuis to hold sealing wax, tweezers, or utensils for sewing; souvenirs, which contained thin ivory tablets for note taking; and shuttles for knotting lace. Gold snuffboxes and boxes decorated with portrait miniatures were prized and frequently given as royal gifts, often to ambassadors or members of the court in lieu of cash payments for their services. Coveted and admired, these boxes were produced from a variety of materials. The best were skillfully made of gold and embellished with diamonds, enameled decoration, lacquer, and other luxurious materials. By the middle of the century, the taking of snuff had become an entrenched social ritual, and the snuffbox, too, had become an important social prop. Snuffboxes were considered highly fashionable accessories, with some merchants advertising new boxes with each change of season. The popularity of snuffboxes extended to all levels of society, and for those who could not afford gold, boxes were produced in less expensive materials such as silver, tortoiseshell, porcelain, or domestically produced lacquer.", "classification": "Metalwork-Gold and Platinum", "accession_number": "17.190.1212", "geographic_location": "Europe,France,Paris", "object_type_material": "Bone,Chalcedony,Enamel,Glass,Gold,Heliotrope,Ivory,Metal,Metalwork,Platinum,Snuff containers,Snuffboxes"}

{"date": "ca. 1430", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/cl/web-large/DP157713.jpg", "title": "Pitcher", "medium": "Tin-glazed earthenware", "source": "http://metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/471799", "culture": "Spanish", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1400\\u20131600", "geography": "Made in probably Manises, Valencia, Spain", "dimensions": "Overall: 18 3/8 x 9 in. (46.7 x 22.9 cm)", "credit_line": "The Cloisters Collection, 1956", "description": "Pitchers with exaggeratedly tall necks, beaklike spouts, and large heavy handles were common in fifteenth-century Spain. This unusually large pitcher, probably made in Manises, the principal center of Spanish lusterware throughout the fifteenth century, holds almost eight quarts, and is a rare example of earthenware technique. Although pitchers were common items of tableware, this particular example, when full, would have been much too heavy to wield conveniently. It therefore might have been used for dispensing wine or water to smaller table pitchers, or for serving wine at large banquets. Its large size and ornamentation have also made it a valuable decorative piece, which perhaps explains its fine state of preservation. The decoration, which includes patterns of pseudo-Kufic script, points to the Muslim origin of all Spanish lusterware. The technique, which originated in the Near East, found its way into Andalusia by the tenth century. By the fifteenth century, piracy and the wars with the Christians had prompted many craftsmen to move northward into the region of Valencia, where all artisans, whether Muslims, Mudejares (Muslims living under a Christian king), or Christians, were allowed to work, and where ships sailed freely to their Mediterranean markets, unhindered by pirates.", "classification": "Ceramics", "accession_number": "56.171.146", "geographic_location": "Europe,Manises,Spain,Valencia", "object_type_material": "Ceramics,Earthenware,Glazing,Pitchers,Pottery,Vessels"}

{"date": "ca. 1770, with one modern panel", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/es/web-large/DP159276.jpg", "title": "Boiserie from the H\\xf4tel Lauzun", "medium": "Carved and painted oak", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/206397", "culture": "French, Paris", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1600\\u20131800", "dimensions": "H. 323-1/2 x W. 323-1/2 x D. 195-3/4 in.  (821.7 x 821.7 x 497.2 cm)", "credit_line": "Purchase, Mr. and Mrs. Charles Wrightsman Gift, 1976", "description": "The design of this Neoclassical paneling incorporates fluted pilasters crowned with Corinthian capitals and three sets of double doors that alternate with carved panels. The latter are embellished below with symmetrical arabesques and vases in low relief and with graceful swags at the top, but they all differ slightly from each other. No eighteenth-century provenance has been discovered for this woodwork, but by 1874 it had been installed in the first-floor (American second floor) gallery of the H\\xf4tel de Lauzun, a seventeenth-century residence on the \\xcele Saint-Louis in Paris. The house was then occupied by the baron J\\xe9r\\xf4me-Fr\\xe9d\\xe9ric Pichon (1812\\u20131896), a well-known collector and bibliophile. Stripped to its bare oak and stained a dark shade of brown, the paneling lined the walls of his library. With its four large windows overlooking the quay and the river Seine, this room was the setting for eccentric parties at which Pichon entertained literary contemporaries such as Charles Baudelaire and Th\\xe9ophile Gautier. The paneling remained in place until the baron\\u2019s grandson, Louis Pichon, acquired the h\\xf4tel in 1905. Having a stricter aesthetic sense and a desire to restore the seventeenthcentury appearance of the gallery, he dismantled and sold the boiserie. It arrived at the Museum in 1976. When microscopic analysis revealed little about the original paint below the stain, the woodwork was repainted in a monochrome gray-green distemper to harmonize with the three grisaille overdoors, which have been associated with the paneling but did not originally belong to it. Showing children representing spring, summer, and winter, they are duplicates of the overdoors representing the four seasons painted about 1787 by Piat Joseph Sauvage (1744\\u20131818) for Queen Marie-Antoinette\\u2019s dairy at Rambouillet.", "classification": "Woodwork", "accession_number": "1976.91.1", "geographic_location": "Europe,France,Paris", "object_type_material": "Oak,Painting,Wood,Woodwork"}

column19: Pendant with Venus and Cupid on a Dolphin
column23: {"date": "ca. 1865\\u201390", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/rl/web-large/DT3587.jpg", "title": "Pendant with Venus and Cupid on a Dolphin", "artist": " Alfred Andr\\xe9 (French, 1839\\u20131919)", "medium": "enameled gold, rubies, and pearls", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/460800", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1800\\u20131900", "dimensions": "H. 11 cm, w. 8.5 cm.", "credit_line": "Robert Lehman Collection, 1975", "description": "The white enameled figures of Venus and Cupid are seated upon a fantastic sea creature. The mythological subject of Venus, goddess of love, accompanied by her son Cupid and a sea creature (signifying her birth from the sea and erotic love), dates back to antiquity and was a popular theme during the Renaissance and later periods. A pendant with such amorous connotations could have served as a nuptial gift. A series of sixteenth-century engravings by Adriaen Collaert depicting designs for pendants in the form of sea monsters attests to the popularity of this motif in Renaissance jewelry. Such engravings likely provided models for the highly skilled European goldsmiths of the nineteenth century, such as Reinhold Vasters and Alfred Andr\\xe9, who produced Renaissance-revival jewelry, of which the present pendant is a striking example.", "classifications": "Jewelry, Precious Metals and Precious Stones", "accession_number": "1975.1.1513", "geographic_location": "Europe,Germany", "artist_maker_culture": "Alfred Andr\\xe9,Reinhold Vasters", "object_type_material": "Costume,Gemstone,Gold,Jewelry,Metal,Pearl,Pendants,Precious stone,Ruby,Stone"}

{"date": "ca. 1850\\u20131550 B.C.", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/eg/web-large/13.180.12_Binder01-01-01.jpg", "title": "Bead Necklace", "medium": "Amethyst", "period": "Late Middle Kingdom\\u2013Second Intermediate Period", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/544419", "dynasty": "Dynasty 12, late\\u201317", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "2000\\u20131000 B.C.", "geography": "From Egypt, Upper Egypt, Thebes, Asasif, Tomb MMA 840, pit in portico, MMA excavations, 1913\\u201314", "dimensions": "L. 64.5 cm (25 3/8 in.)", "credit_line": "Rogers Fund and Edward S. Harkness Gift, 1913", "description": "This necklace was found with other pieces of jewelry in the plundered chamber reached by a shaft in the portico of a rock-cut tomb in the Asasif section of the Theban necropolis.  Among the finds were parts of a rectangular wooden coffin with green hieroglyphs on a yellow background as well as a few remains of one or more model wooden boat(s), three scarabs (13.180.8- .10), two anhydrite toilet vessels (13.180.19a- .c, .20) and the group of jewelry items (13.180.1- .18a- .l) striking for the extensive use of silver.  Dates that can be ascertained by stylistic comparisons to some of the objects range from the late Middle Kingdom (ca. 1850-1700 B. C.) to the late Second Intermediate Period (ca. 1580-1550 B. C.).  A number of clay pots (28.3.239- .241 now in the Oriental Institute Museum, Chicago) from the area of the tomb but not with certainty identified as found inside the shaft and chamber from which the jewelry was obtained date to the late Second Intermediate Period.", "accession_number": "13.180.12", "geographic_location": "Africa,Egypt,Thebes,Upper Egypt", "object_type_material": "Amethyst,Costume,Jewelry,Necklaces"}

column23: {"date": "1801", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/dp/web-large/DP254722.jpg", "title": "Oeuvres de Jean Racine", "author": "Written by Jean Racine (French, baptized 1639\\u20131699 Paris)", "medium": "Printed book with engraved illustrations", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/381619", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1800\\u20131900", "engraver": "Engraved by Jean-Baptiste-Michel Dupr\\xe9el (French, active 1787\\u20131817)", "publisher": "Published by Pierre Didot l'ain\\xe9 (French, 1761\\u20131853) , Paris", "dimensions": "Overall: 19 11/16 x 13 3/4 x 2 3/4 in. (50 x 35 x 7 cm)", "credit_line": "Rogers, Harris Brisbane Dick, and The Elisha Whittelsey Funds; and Gift of John Sise, by exchange, 1958", "description": "This is the first volume of Didot's three-volume The Works of Racine. It inaugurated the third part of his suite of luxury volumes known as the \"Louvre editions.\" Along with the first installment in the project, The Works of Virgil (1798), it features full-page illustrations instead of headpieces. The illustrations were designed by six painters and two sculptors, and engraved by a host of printmakers. Each play was illustrated wholly by one artist, so that a continuity of style and interpretation was established within each unit of the book. This consistency was not extended to the printmakers, however, which perhaps resulted in more variation than Didot had intended for the images.", "illustrator": "Illustrated by baron Fran\\xe7ois G\\xe9rard (French, Rome 1770\\u20131837 Paris)", "published_in": "Paris", "classification": "Books", "accession_number": "58.635.1(1)", "geographic_location": "Europe,France,Paris", "artist_maker_culture": "Antoine Denis Chaudet,Pierre Didot l'ain\\xe9,Jean-Baptiste-Michel Dupr\\xe9el,baron Fran\\xe7ois G\\xe9rard,Anne Louis Girodet-Trioson,Jean Guillaume Moitte,Pierre Paul Prud'hon,Jean Racine,Taunai", "object_type_material": "Books,Engraving,Illustrations"}

column19: Saint John the Baptist Bearing Witness
column23: {"date": "ca. 1506\\u20137", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ep/web-large/DT11166.jpg", "title": "Saint John the Baptist Bearing Witness", "artist": "Workshop of Francesco Granacci (Italian, Villamagna 1469\\u20131543 Florence)", "medium": "Oil and gold on wood", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/436568", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1400\\u20131600", "dimensions": "29 3/4 x 82 1/2 in. (75.6 x 209.6 cm)", "credit_line": "Purchase, Gwynne Andrews, Harris Brisbane Dick, Dodge, Fletcher, and Rogers Funds, funds from various donors, Ella Morris de Peyster Gift, Mrs. Donald Oenslager Gift, and Gifts in memory of Robert Lehman, 1970", "description": "This panel concluded the series to which the adjacent picture belonged. It shows Saint John the Baptist preaching. The two Pharisees at the left gesture towards the advancing figure of Christ. A work of great distinction, the picture is in many respects superior to the companion panel and must be by another artist. Collaborations of this sort were common in the Renaissance. A tentative attribution has been made to Raffaello Botticini, whose later works, however, never attain this quality. The affinities some of the figures show with the Doni Tondo of Michelangelo further point up the stature of the piece. Michelangelo and Granacci were friends and fellow pupils in the workshop of Domenico Ghirlandaio.", "classification": "Paintings", "accession_number": "1970.134.2", "geographic_location": "Europe,Italy", "artist_maker_culture": "Francesco Granacci", "object_type_material": "Gold,Metal,Oil paint,Paintings"}

{"date": "1884", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ph/web-large/DP111353.jpg", "title": "Horse", "artist": "Ottomar Ansch\\xfctz (German, Lissa (Leszno, Poland) 1846\\u20131907 Berlin)", "medium": "Albumen silver print", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/266656", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1800\\u20131900", "credit_line": "Purchase, The Horace W. Goldsmith Foundation Gift, through Joyce and Robert Menschel, 1992", "description": "In the last quarter of the nineteenth century, photographers and scientists became interested in arresting action on film. Their studies revealed movement beyond what the human eye could see. One of the most skilled innovators in the field was Ottomar Ansch\\xfctz, whose detailed photographs of animal locomotion caught the attention of the German government. Commissioned by the War Ministry, Ansch\\xfctz recorded horses and their riders at the elite Military Institute in Hannover. This photograph of a soldier reining in his steed, its untamed mane frozen in midair, was previously in the collection of the Catalan muralist Josep Maria Sert. The grid that Sert added to the photograph indicates he may have used it as a reference for his artwork.", "classification": "Photographs", "accession_number": "1992.5013", "geographic_location": "Europe,Germany", "artist_maker_culture": "Ottomar Ansch\\xfctz", "object_type_material": "Albumen silver prints,Photographs"}

column19: Trial piece of Akhenaten, on the reverse a horse's head
column23: {"date": "ca. 1353\\u20131336 B.C.", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/eg/web-large/DP109392.jpg", "reign": "reign of Akhenaten", "title": "Trial piece of Akhenaten, on the reverse a horse's head", "medium": "Limestone", "period": "New Kingdom, Amarna Period", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/544527", "dynasty": "Dynasty 18", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "2000\\u20131000 B.C.", "geography": "From Egypt, Middle Egypt, Amarna (Akhetaten), Sculptors' workshop near south end of the town, Petrie/Carter excavations, 1891\\u201392", "dimensions": "h. 17 cm (6 11/16 in); w. 13.5 cm (5 5/16 in)", "credit_line": "Gift of Edward S. Harkness, 1921", "description": "This unfinished study of the head of Akhenaten was one of a number excavated by Flinders Petrie and Howard Carter in 1891\\u201392 from the sculptors' workshops at Tell el-Amarna, the new royal capital founded by Akhenaten. It came to the Museum from the collection of Lord Amherst, who sponsored the excavations. It shows the king in the later, more naturalistic Amarna style. The characteristic attributes of the portraits of the king\\u2014long almond-shaped eyes, full lips, elongated jaw and chin, and sloping brow\\u2014are present but without the exaggeration of the earlier portraits. These studies may have served as models for or practice pieces by the sculptors carving the reliefs for the huge Aten temples that the king was building in order to worship according to his own unorthodox interpretation of the religion of ancient Egypt; it is also possible that some may have been employed as donation pieces.", "accession_number": "21.9.13", "geographic_location": "Africa,Amarna,Egypt,Upper Egypt", "object_type_material": "Limestone"}

{"date": "ca. 1390\\u201395", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/cl/web-large/DP124049.jpg", "title": "Bust of the Virgin", "medium": "Terracotta with paint", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/476711", "culture": "Bohemian", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1000\\u20131400", "geography": "Made in Prague, Bohemia", "dimensions": "12 13/16 x 8 13/16 x 5 7/16 in. (32.5 x 22.4 x 13.8 cm)", "credit_line": "The Cloisters Collection, 2005", "description": "With regal elegance and a tender face, this image of the Virgin constituted the upper portion of a standing or enthroned figure that would have been accompanied by the child Jesus. Artists working in clay would normally divide a large sculpture horizontally with a wire before firing to ensure that it dried evenly. The sections would then be reassembled with mortar disguised under the paint. This is the only terracotta sculpture attributed to medieval Prague.", "classification": "Sculpture-Ceramics", "accession_number": "2005.393", "geographic_location": "Bohemia,Czech Republic,Europe", "object_type_material": "Busts,Ceramics,Clay,Figures,Sculpture,Terracotta"}

{"date": "ca. 1600", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/is/web-large/DP251275.jpg", "title": "Portrait of a Man", "artist": "Attributed to Riza-yi `Abbasi (Persian, ca. 1565\\u20131635)", "medium": "Ink, opaque watercolor, and gold on paper", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/446570", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "geography": "Attributed to Iran", "dimensions": "H. 8 3/8 in. (21.3 cm)\\r\\nW. 5 1/4 in. (13.3 cm)", "credit_line": "Gift of Alexander Smith Cochran, 1913", "description": "Despite the absence of a signature, this portrait of a man pulling a shawl around his shoulders bears many of the stylistic hallmarks of the artist Riza working at the court of Shah \\u2018Abbas I around 1600. The rounded cheeks and slight double chin appear on many of Riza\\u2019s paintings of youths, but the shape of the figure\\u2019s small \"bee-stung\" lips is nearly identical to that of several other figures from the same period. The fineness of the artist\\u2019s brushstrokes on which his contemporaries remarked is evident in the soft fuzz of the figure\\u2019s fur hat and delicately painted eyebrows. Even the gold x\\u2019s on his robe are specific to this period of Riza\\u2019s career and presumably reflect a style of that moment. Such paintings were made for inclusion in albums and were particularly popular in the seventeenth century when portraiture became one of the favorite genres of Persian painting.", "object_name": "Illustrated single work", "classification": "Codices", "accession_number": "13.228.36", "geographic_location": "Asia,Iran", "artist_maker_culture": "Riza-yi `Abbasi", "object_type_material": "Codices,Gold,Ink,Manuscripts,Metal,Paper,Watercolors"}

column19: A Tumultuous Assembly. Numerical Sensibility (Une Assemblée tumultueuse. Sensibilité numérique) published in Les mots en liberté futuristes
column23: {"date": "1919", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/dp/web-large/DP371750.jpg", "title": "A Tumultuous Assembly. Numerical Sensibility (Une Assembl\\xe9e tumultueuse. Sensibilit\\xe9 num\\xe9rique) published in Les mots en libert\\xe9 futuristes", "artist": "Filippo Tommaso Marinetti (Italian, born Egypt, Alexandria 1876\\u20131944 Bellagio, Italy)", "medium": "Letterpress", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/345679", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1900\\u2013present", "dimensions": "10 1/2 x 13 in.  (26.7 x 33.0 cm)", "credit_line": "Gift of W. Michael Sheehe, 1995", "description": "A Tumultuous Assembly: Numerical Sensibility is an example of tavole parolibere (free-word pictures). In this print, the subject of which is Italy\\u2019s victory in World War I, Marinetti drew from visual collage and parole in libert\\xe0 (words-in-freedom) and eschewed regulations of grammar and syntax to create a work that can be interpreted both visually and aurally. A Tumultuous Assembly: Numerical Sensibility liberates numbers, signs, letters, and images from their functional responsibilities, exaggerates forms, and juxtaposes diverse elements, thereby producing unexpected associations. The Futurists celebrated the potential of war, drawing analogies between weaponry, such as torpedoes and bombs, and Futurist poetry. Here, Marinetti combined innovative typography, found elements (such as the image of the drummer boy on the left and the strips of letters and numbers throughout the composition), and dramatic variations in scale to create a dynamic composition representing a celebrating crowd.", "classification": "Prints", "accession_number": "1995.511.2", "geographic_location": "Europe,Italy,Venice", "artist_maker_culture": "Filippo Tommaso Marinetti", "object_type_material": "Prints"}

column19: The Holy Family with the Infant Saint John the Baptist
column23: {"date": "ca. 1524\\u201326", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ep/web-large/DP255071.jpg", "title": "The Holy Family with the Infant Saint John the Baptist", "artist": "Perino del Vaga (Pietro Buonaccorsi) (Italian, Florence 1501\\u20131547 Rome)", "medium": "Oil on wood", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/441227", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1400\\u20131600", "dimensions": "34 3/4 x 25 5/8 in. (88.3 x 65.1 cm)", "credit_line": "Purchase, Acquisitions Fund, Mr. and Mrs. Mark Fisch, Denise and Andrew Saul, and Friends of European Paintings Gifts, Gwynne Andrews Fund, Mr. and Mrs. J. Tomilson Hill, Jon and Barbara Landau, Charles and Jessie Price, Hester Diamond, and Fern and George Wachter Gifts, 2011", "description": "Florentine by birth, Perino del Vaga was trained in Raphael's workshop in Rome, where he soon became one of the most inventive artists of his generation. This is a rare early work and dates from the mid-1520s. The young Christ holds the traditional symbols of a goldfinch (symbolic of the Resurrection) and a cherry (signifying the delights of the blessed). More unusually, the young Saint John is crowned with grape leaves and wears a leopard skin, usually associated with the ancient god Bacchus. column23: {"date": "ca. 1381", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/md/web-large/DT135.jpg", "title": "Tomb Effigy Bust of Marie de France (1327-41), daughter of Charles IV of France and Jeanne d'Evreux", "artist": "Jean de Li\\xe8ge (Franco-Netherlandish, active ca. 1361\\u2013died 1381)", "medium": "Marble with lead inlays", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/467705", "culture": "French", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1000\\u20131400", "geography": "Made in \\xcele de France", "dimensions": "Overall (without base): 12 1/4 x 12 3/4 x 6 3/16 in. (31.1 x 32.4 x 15.7 cm)", "credit_line": "Gift of George Blumenthal, 1941", "description": "The Royal Abbey of Saint-Denis was the burial church for the rulers of France and their families. This elegant image once formed a part of the tomb effigy of the princess Marie de France (1326\\u20131341) and her sister Blanche de France (1328\\u20131393), daughters of Charles IV (1294\\u20131328) and Jeanne d\\u2019Evreux (before 1313\\u20131371). Although Marie died young, her effigy was not carved until about 1381 by the court sculptor Jean de Li\\xe8ge. The image here of the tomb is from a drawing made before 1715. Many of the tombs in the abbey were vandalized in the wake of the French Revolution. Originally the head rested upon a stone pillow, and the princess wore a metal crown. Her braided hair is arranged in the courtly fashion contemporary with the carving of the bust.", "classification": "Sculpture-Stone", "accession_number": "41.100.132", "geographic_location": "Europe,France", "artist_maker_culture": "Jean de Li\\xe8ge", "object_type_material": "Busts,Figures,Lead,Marble,Metal,Sculpture,Stone"}

column23: {"date": "1750", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/es/web-large/39699.jpg", "maker": "Claude de Villers (master 1718, died 1755)", "title": "Snuffbox", "medium": "Gold, mother-of-pearl, ivory, enamel", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/193915", "culture": "French, Paris", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1600\\u20131800", "purveyor": "Joseph Vallayer (master 1750, died 1770)", "dimensions": "3 1/8 x 2 3/8 in. (7.9 x 6cm)", "credit_line": "Gift of J. Pierpont Morgan, 1917", "description": "In eighteenth-century Europe, Paris led the production of high-quality luxury goods. Parisian goldsmiths made a wide range of small, personal articles such as snuffboxes; \\xe9tuis to hold sealing wax, tweezers, or utensils for sewing; souvenirs, which contained thin ivory tablets for note taking; and shuttles for knotting lace. Gold snuffboxes and boxes decorated with portrait miniatures were prized and frequently given as royal gifts, often to ambassadors or members of the court in lieu of cash payments for their services. Coveted and admired, these boxes were produced from a variety of materials. The best were skillfully made of gold and embellished with diamonds, enameled decoration, lacquer, and other luxurious materials. By the middle of the century, the taking of snuff had become an entrenched social ritual, and the snuffbox, too, had become an important social prop. Snuffboxes were considered highly fashionable accessories, with some merchants advertising new boxes with each change of season. The popularity of snuffboxes extended to all levels of society, and for those who could not afford gold, boxes were produced in less expensive materials such as silver, tortoiseshell, porcelain, or domestically produced lacquer.", "classification": "Metalwork-Gold and Platinum", "accession_number": "17.190.1245", "geographic_location": "Europe,France,Paris", "artist_maker_culture": "Joseph Vallayer,Claude de Villers", "object_type_material": "Bone,Enamel,Gold,Ivory,Metal,Metalwork,Mother of pearl,Platinum,Snuff containers,Snuffboxes"}

column23: {"date": "cast between 1844 and 1856", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/es/web-large/SF2005_108_2.jpg", "title": "Baptiste-Henri Gr\\xe9goire, called L'Abb\\xe9 Gr\\xe9goire (1750\\u20131831)", "artist": "Medalist: Pierre Jean David d'Angers (French, Angers 1788\\u20131856 Paris)", "medium": "Bronze", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/231230", "culture": "French", "founder": "Cast by Eck et Durand", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1800\\u20131900", "dimensions": "Diameter: 6 in. (15.2 cm)", "credit_line": "Gift of Joseph G. Reinis, 2005", "description": "Pierre-Jean David d\\u2019Angers was the most prolific and one of the most important French sculptors of the first half of the nineteenth century. Throughout his almost fifty-year career (1819\\u20131856) David remained true to his conviction that sculptural monuments dedicated to the achievements of great men and women most permanently and vividly express the greatness of a people. He continuously sought commissions for monuments portraying historical and contemporary figures whom he admired in order to commit their contributions to posterity. His most famous public commission, the figurative pediment of the Pantheon in Paris (1830\\u20131837), which commemorates great men and was dedicated by a grateful nation, exemplifies these life-long principles. \\n\\nDavid d\\u2019Angers extended his definition of public monuments to include portrait medallions. In the 1820s he dedicated himself to a personal campaign of creating contemporary and retrospective medallic portraits of illustrious sitters. By the end of his life David had executed almost five-hundred portrait medallions, frequently travelling great distances to model his sitters from life. The medallions most often were not commissioned. David himself chose whom he deemed worthy of inclusion into his medallic pantheon. David also did not profit from the portraits. He generally delivered his wax models to professional founders for casting and dissemination through sale.", "classification": "Medals and Plaquettes", "accession_number": "2005.108.2", "geographic_location": "Europe,France", "artist_maker_culture": "Pierre Jean David d'Angers,Eck et Durand", "object_type_material": "Bronze,Copper alloy,Medallions,Medals,Metal,Plaquettes,Sculpture"}

column19: A View Near the Arco Scuro, Looking Towards the Villa Medici, Rome
column23: {"date": "1785", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/dp/web-large/DP238000.jpg", "title": "A View Near the Arco Scuro, Looking Towards the Villa Medici, Rome", "artist": "Francis Towne (British, Isleworth, Middlesex 1739\\u20131816 Exeter)", "medium": "Watercolor over graphite with pen and brown ink, on laid paper", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/395055", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1600\\u20131800", "dimensions": "sheet: 12 13/16 x 18 7/8 in. (32.5 x 48 cm)", "credit_line": "Purchase, Walter and Leonore Annenberg Acquisitions Endowment and Harry G. Sperling Funds, 2010", "description": "Towne left Exeter, in southwestern England, to visit Italy in 1780-81. After his return, a former student commissioned this Roman view showing a steep road falling away over a hill toward the Villa Medici (now the Acad\\xe9mie Fran\\xe7aise). Towne made a series of sketches along the rural road behind the villa in November 1780 and used one as the basis of the later composition. His interest lay not in famous landmarks but in capturing effects of light falling across overgrown foliage, contrasted with patches of deep shade. Employing an innovative method to create tone, he began with layers of pure color then moved on to pigments mixed with brown or black. This reversal of the traditional order allowed greater subtlety, particularly in the darks.", "classification": "Drawings", "accession_number": "2010.439", "geographic_location": "Europe,United Kingdom", "artist_maker_culture": "Francis Towne", "object_type_material": "Drawings,Graphite,Ink,Laid paper,Paper,Watercolors"}

{"date": "4th\\u20137th century", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ao/web-large/DP102127.jpg", "title": "Double-Chambered Bottle", "medium": "Ceramic", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/316001", "culture": "Bahia", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "geography": "Ecuador", "dimensions": "H x W: 7 1/4 x 10in. (18.4 x 25.4cm)", "credit_line": "Gift of Peggy and Tessim Zorach, 1988", "description": "Double-chambered bottles were a common vessel form among the Bah\\xeda people of coastal Ecuador. The chambers, which were round and squat or tall and slender, as here, were joined at the bottom by a tube and at the top by a strap handle. A single, narrow spout tops one of the chambers, while the other vessel serves as a base for modeled figurative sculptures. On this bottle, two fantastic iguana-like creatures sit side by side at the top, their thick, long tails hanging down the side of the container. The iguanas wear necklaces and head crests; long streamers emerge from their open, fanged mouths; their bodies have dorsal crests and winglike elements projecting on the sides. The dull, bumpy surface of the animals, covered with light green pigment, contrasts with the smooth, burnished finish of the red-slipped chambers. The hollow iguanas function as whistles, their several holes producing a sound when the liquid in the bottle is poured out. Iguanas or dragonlike creatures and serpents are frequent motifs in Bah\\xeda art and seem to have played an important role in local mythology.", "classification": "Ceramics-Containers", "accession_number": "1988.117.7", "geographic_location": "Ecuador,South America", "object_type_material": "Bottles,Ceramics,Vessels"}

column17: Thomas Eakins (American, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania 1844–1916 Philadelphia, Pennsylvania)
column23: {"date": "1883", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ph/web-large/DT11884.jpg", "title": "[Three Boys Wading in a Creek]", "artist": "Thomas Eakins (American, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania 1844\\u20131916 Philadelphia, Pennsylvania)", "medium": "Platinum print ", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/271868", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1800\\u20131900", "credit_line": "Gift of Charles Bregler, 1944", "description": "In 1882, Thomas Eakins was promoted to the post of director of schools at the Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts, where he became known as a charismatic and innovative teacher who advocated intensive study of the nude figure. Committed to teaching close observation through every means possible, Eakins turned his school into a laboratory of photographic experimentation. He and his students (male and female) made negatives of each other-in lithe repose or in action, nude or in costume. At times, Eakins must have realized that he was pushing the limits of Philadelphia decorum. This small 4 x 5 albumen silver print shows several of Eakins' nephews playing in a creek on the property of the artist's sister Frances and her husband, William J. Crowell. In the 1880s, Eakins spent much of his free time at the Crowell family home in Avondale, Pennsylvania, thirty miles southwest of Philadelphia. Distant from urban distractions, the idyllic farm soon became a refuge for him. The Crowell children delighted Eakins and he made many photographs of their spirited games.", "classification": "Photographs", "accession_number": "44.75.7", "geographic_location": "North and Central America,United States", "artist_maker_culture": "Thomas Eakins", "object_type_material": "Metal,Photographs,Platinum,Platinum prints,Prints"}

column23: {"date": "1863", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ph/web-large/DP274779.jpg", "title": "Confederate Method of Destroying Rail Roads at McCloud Mill, Virginia", "artist": "Andrew Joseph Russell (American, 1830\\u20131902)", "medium": "Albumen silver print from glass negative", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/267963", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1800\\u20131900", "dimensions": "Image: 16.2 \\xd7 19.6 cm (6 3/8 \\xd7 7 11/16 in.)", "credit_line": "Harris Brisbane Dick Fund, 1933", "description": "Russell made several photographs of the discovery by the Union army of the simple but effective method developed by the Confederates to destroy Union railroad track. Using the ties as fuel, the soldiers stacked the iron rails in X formations and burned them until they could be twisted and made unusable. Federal engineers employed similar tactics to destroy Southern railroads, and this photograph has been published, inaccurately, as \\u201cSherman\\u2019s Neckties.\\u201d The title refers to Union General William Tecumseh Sherman, who during the Atlanta Campaign on July 18, 1864, gave the following explicit order to his corps: \\u201cOfficers should be instructed that bars simply bent may be used again, but if when red hot they are twisted out of line they cannot be used again. Pile the ties into shape for a bonfire, put the rails across and when red hot in the middle, let a man at each end twist the bar so that its surface becomes spiral.\\u201d", "classification": "Photographs", "accession_number": "33.65.175", "former_attribution": "Formerly attributed to Mathew B. column19: John Frederick Blumenbach (1752–1841), German physician and physiologist
column23: {"date": "1834", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/es/web-large/31525.jpg", "title": "John Frederick Blumenbach (1752\\u20131841), German physician and physiologist", "artist": "Pierre Jean David d'Angers (French, Angers 1788\\u20131856 Paris)", "medium": "Bronze, cast - single", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/188409", "culture": "French", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1800\\u20131900", "dimensions": "Diameter: 6 in. (15.2 cm)", "credit_line": "Gift of Samuel P. Avery, 1898", "description": "Pierre-Jean David d\\u2019Angers was the most prolific and one of the most important French sculptors of the first half of the nineteenth century. Throughout his almost fifty-year career (1819\\u20131856) David remained true to his conviction that sculptural monuments dedicated to the achievements of great men and women most permanently and vividly express the greatness of a people. He continuously sought commissions for monuments portraying historical and contemporary figures whom he admired in order to commit their contributions to posterity. His most famous public commission, the figurative pediment of the Pantheon in Paris (1830\\u20131837), which commemorates great men and was dedicated by a grateful nation, exemplifies these life-long principles. \\n\\nDavid d\\u2019Angers extended his definition of public monuments to include portrait medallions. In the 1820s he dedicated himself to a personal campaign of creating contemporary and retrospective medallic portraits of illustrious sitters. By the end of his life David had executed almost five-hundred portrait medallions, frequently travelling great distances to model his sitters from life. The medallions most often were not commissioned. David himself chose whom he deemed worthy of inclusion into his medallic pantheon. David also did not profit from the portraits. He generally delivered his wax models to professional founders for casting and dissemination through sale.", "classification": "Medals and Plaquettes", "accession_number": "98.7.2", "geographic_location": "Europe,France", "artist_maker_culture": "Pierre Jean David d'Angers", "object_type_material": "Bronze,Copper alloy,Medallions,Medals,Metal,Plaquettes,Sculpture"}

{"date": "early 17th century", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/es/web-large/sf91-1-118a.jpg", "title": "Plate", "medium": "Tin-glazed and luster-painted earthenware", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/187251", "culture": "Spanish, Valencia", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1600\\u20131800", "dimensions": "Diameter: 8 in. (20.3 cm)", "credit_line": "Edward C. Moore Collection, Bequest of Edward C. Moore, 1891", "description": "Tin-glazed earthenware, of which lusterware is one type, was developed in the Middle East in the ninth and tenth centuries to imitate the porcelains produced in China. The opaque white glaze concealed the clay body, which could range from pale buff to brick red, allowing for brilliant effects created by painting the white surface with metal oxides that fired to a range of colors. This technique, as well as the use of metallic luster\\u2014an iridescent, coppery painted glaze\\u2014spread throughout the Muslim world, arriving among the potters of Valencia in the thirteenth century. The so-called Hispano-Moresque lusterware, with its fusion of Islamic and Gothic styles and motifs, often in shaped imitating those of metal vessels, was treasured by the elite in Spain during the fifteenth century and exported to the courts of Europe. The Valencian industry declined in the late sixteenth century, as colorful Italian Renaissance maiolica gained in popularity among the fashionable and as Spanish centers were founded to produce versions of its pictorial forms. Adding to this decline was the expulsion from Valencia in 1609 of all the remaining Moriscos (Muslims converted to Christianity), though Christian potters reestablished the industry shortly thereafter.", "classification": "Ceramics-Pottery", "accession_number": "91.1.118", "geographic_location": "Europe,Spain,Valencia", "object_type_material": "Ceramics,Dishes,Earthenware,Glazing,Luster,Painting,Plates,Pottery"}

column17: Anton Raphael Mengs (German, Ústi nad Labem (Aussig) 1728–1779 Rome)
column23: {"date": "1776", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ep/web-large/DP240926.jpg", "title": "Self-Portrait", "artist": "Anton Raphael Mengs (German, \\xdasti nad Labem (Aussig) 1728\\u20131779 Rome)", "medium": "Oil on canvas", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/441115", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1600\\u20131800", "dimensions": "35 1/2 x 25 7/8 in. (90 x 65.5 cm)", "credit_line": "Harris Brisbane Dick Fund, 2010", "description": "Born in Bohemia, Mengs became the most important painter in Dresden, Rome, and Madrid in the third quarter of the eighteenth century. Whereas Mengs's portraits of prominent sitters are notable for their delicacy, meticulous detail, and refined beauty, his self-portraits are essays in truthfulness. The discolored swelling on his forehead is a physical defect visible from about 1760; declining health forced him to leave his position as court painter at Madrid in 1769, though he returned there between 1774 and 1777. This self-portrait was painted in Madrid in 1776 and dispatched to Genoa; three other, inferior versions are known.", "classification": "Paintings", "accession_number": "2010.445", "geographic_location": "Europe,Germany", "artist_maker_culture": "Anton Raphael Mengs", "object_type_material": "Canvas,Oil paint,Paintings"}

Alternating stripes of sheer material was a prominent configuration at the time for both women's and girl's dresses.  It is obvious that this dress was made with a great deal of detail and thought, which can be seen in the double ruffles of the underdress sleeves as well as the overdress sleeves, and the multiple ruffles of the skirt and the underskirt.  The low bustle effect in back is appropriate for a young girl, and the long-waisted silhouette was typical of the time.  The interior ties of the skirt create more of a bustle effect.", "accession_number": "2009.300.3208a, b", "geographic_location": "North and Central America,United States", "object_type_material": "Costume,Dresses,Silk"}

{"date": "ca. 1160s\\u201370s", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/is/web-large/DP368487.jpg", "title": "Hexagonal Tile Ensemble with Sphinx", "medium": "Stonepaste; over- and underglaze-painted, gilded\\r\\n", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/452817", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1000\\u20131400", "geography": "From Turkey, Konya", "dimensions": "H. 9 1/4 in. (23.5 cm)\\r\\nW. 8 1/4 in. (21 cm)\\r\\nD. 1 1/8 in. (2.9 cm)", "credit_line": "Gift of Mr. and Mrs. Jack A. Josephson, 1976", "description": "By the early twentieth century, the two-story Konya K\\xf6\\u015fk had largely fallen into ruin, but architectural fragments speak to its former artistic sophistication and lavish polychrome ornamentation. The upper story of this Rum Seljuq \\u201ccitadel-palace\\u201d was dominated by an iwan with balconies on three sides facing outward over the sultanate\\u2019s capital, Konya, thereby functioning as both a belvedere and a point from which the sultan could consider his dominion. The luxurious mina\\u02d2i ceramic technique of these tiles is reminiscent of that associated with the luxury vessels made in Kashan, Iran. The stucco reliefs also recall the artistic language developing both in the eastern and western parts of the Seljuq realm, which eventually extended into Christian lands, as seen in comparable stucco reliefs found at the Armenian capital at Ani. The imagery of real and fantastic animals and scenes of equestrian combat aimed to re-create an earthly paradise or the ideal life and just dominion of the sovereign presiding over this cosmos. It also offered supernatural and magical protection to the ruler, his entourage, and the sultanate. The Konya K\\xf6\\u015fk, although situated in an urban environment, evoked the ideal natural setting awaiting the sultan at his country pavilions as well as the paradisiacal ideal awaiting him in heaven.", "object_name": "Tile panel", "classification": "Ceramics-Tiles", "accession_number": "1976.245", "geographic_location": "Asia,Konya,Turkey", "object_type_material": "Ceramics,Gilt,Painting,Panels,Tile,Underglazing"}

", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/460343", "culture": "Florentine", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1000\\u20131400", "dimensions": "Overall, 52.6 x 18.4 cm; sight, 46.2 x 12 cm; engaged.", "credit_line": "Robert Lehman Collection, 1975", "description": "Spinello Aretino (1350/52-1410) painted these two panels depiciting Saints Philip and James the Greater(?) for an altarpiece for Monte Oliveto Maggiore near Siena. Other panels from the same polyptych survive in the Pinacoteca Nazionale, Siena; the Sz\\xe9pmuv\\xe9szeti M\\xfazeum, Budapest; and the Fogg Art Museum, Cambridge, Massachusetts. Another pilaster panel like the two in the Robert Lehman Collection was sold at Sotheby's in London in 1982. An inscription across the base of the altarpiece frame, recorded by Giorgio Vasari when it was still intact, memorialized the frame carver and the gilder alongside the painter: \"Simone Cini Fiorentino fece l'intaglio, Gabriello Saracini la messe d'oro e Spinello di Luca d'Arezzo la dipinse l'anno 1385.\" The three artists received equal payments for their work. The pastiglia Solomonic columns on these two panels are not as well defined as those on 1975.1.23b, which are subtly delineated with punching. Evans (British, London 1853–1943 London),  Bookplate designed by Aubrey Vincent Beardsley (British, Brighton, Sussex 1872–1898 Menton),  Bookplate designed by Frederick Colin Tilney (British, 1870–1951),  Unknown (British), Ernest Radford (British, active late 19th century), Theodore Watts-Dunton (British, 1832–1914),  Sir Sydney Cockerell (1910–1957)
column23: {"date": "1896", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ph/web-large/DP136681.jpg", "title": "Bed Morris Was Born In", "artist": " Unknown (British)", "author": "Ernest Radford (British, active late 19th century)", "medium": "Platinum print", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/675540", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1800\\u20131900", "credit_line": "Purchase, David Hunter McAlpin Fund, 1968", "description": "Kelmscott Manor was the country home of William Morris (1834-1896), poet, craftsman, designer, socialist reformer, and founder of the English Arts and Crafts movement. He and his wife Jane shared the house with the Pre-Raphaelite painter Dante Gabriel Rossetti from 1871 to 1874, and it remained a country retreat for Morris and the artists and intellectuals in his circle until his death. At Morris' request, the bookseller and photographer Evans visited the old gray manor on the banks of the Thames in order to photograph it. This rare album, one of only two known to exist, was assembled by the photographer and contains thirty-one platinum prints, each carefully mounted on colored papers. In this photograph, Evans infused the bare and rambling space of the attic with a sense of harmony and spirituality that would later characterize his photographs of England's great cathedrals.", "correspondent": " Sir Sydney Cockerell (1910\\u20131957)", "classification": "Albums", "accession_number": "68.519 (14)", "geographic_location": "Europe,United Kingdom", "artist_maker_culture": "Aubrey Vincent Beardsley,Sir Sydney Cockerell,Frederick H. It depicts a type of armor that disappeared toward the third quarter of the thirteenth century. {"date": " ca. 1500", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/es/web-large/25120.jpg", "title": "Plateau", "medium": "Tin-glazed and luster-painted earthenware", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/187797", "culture": "Spanish, Valencia", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1400\\u20131600", "dimensions": "Diameter: 17 in. (43.2 cm)", "credit_line": "Gift of Henry G. Marquand, 1894", "description": "Tin-glazed earthenware, of which lusterware is one type, was developed in the Middle East in the ninth and tenth centuries to imitate the porcelains produced in China. The opaque white glaze concealed the clay body, which could range from pale buff to brick red, allowing for brilliant effects created by painting the white surface with metal oxides that fired to a range of colors. This technique, as well as the use of metallic luster\\u2014an iridescent, coppery painted glaze\\u2014spread throughout the Muslim world, arriving among the potters of Valencia in the thirteenth century. The so-called Hispano-Moresque lusterware, with its fusion of Islamic and Gothic styles and motifs, often in shaped imitating those of metal vessels, was treasured by the elite in Spain during the fifteenth century and exported to the courts of Europe. The Valencian industry declined in the late sixteenth century, as colorful Italian Renaissance maiolica gained in popularity among the fashionable and as Spanish centers were founded to produce versions of its pictorial forms. Adding to this decline was the expulsion from Valencia in 1609 of all the remaining Moriscos (Muslims converted to Christianity), though Christian potters reestablished the industry shortly thereafter.", "classification": "Ceramics-Pottery", "accession_number": "94.4.244", "geographic_location": "Europe,Spain,Valencia", "object_type_material": "Ceramics,Earthenware,Glazing,Luster,Painting,Plateaus,Pottery"}

An expanded compass of 5-1/2 octaves is possible by a design that has keys extend under the soundboard. Tuning pins have moved from the right side, where they were crowded and far from the lowest key to a convenient arrangement along the back. This piano has no damper control; the pedal opens the lid flap over the soundboard when the main lid panel is closed. Broadwood replaced hand stops by pedals around 1785. By the 1790s his firm was making about 400 squares and 100 grands annually.", "classification": "Chordophone-Zither-struck-piano", "accession_number": "1982.76", "geographic_location": "England,Europe,London,United Kingdom", "artist_maker_culture": "John Broadwood & Sons", "object_type_material": "Bone,Boxwood,Brass,Chordophones,Copper alloy,Ebony,Iron,Iron and iron alloy,Ivory,Mahogany,Metal,Musical instruments,Pianos,Veneer,Wood,Zithers"}

{"date": "ca. 1530\\u201340", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/es/web-large/DP-156-001.jpg", "title": "Capricorn (section of a zodiac frieze)", "medium": "Bronze", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/231027", "culture": "Italian, Venice", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1400\\u20131600", "dimensions": "Overall (confirmed): 6 1/2 \\xd7 7 7/8 \\xd7 1 7/8 in. (16.5 \\xd7 20 \\xd7 4.8 cm)", "credit_line": "European Sculpture and Decorative Arts Fund, 2004", "description": "Typically Venetian are the punched grounds against which the forms dance on these frieze sections. More sinuously elegant than reliefs by leading Venetian bronze sculptors of the generation active about 1500\\u20131520\\u2014Alessandro Leopardi, Vittore Gambello (known as Camelio), and the Master of the Barbarigo Reliefs\\u2014the present two (see also Sagittarius, 2004.440.2) may date slightly later but are still informed by High Renaissance standards of expression and orga nization. The band to which they belonged was exceptionally large\\u2014on the basis of these two of the zodiac's twelve signs, the original ring has been projected at thirty-two to thirty-eight inches in diameter. Its function can only be surmised. At Sagittarius's top left are faint remains of an inscription, which is mostly filed away. One can discern F. CITA0 (abbreviations formai and anno) and a space for numerals, of which the last may be a two. When first recorded in the mid-nineteenth century, in the fabled Fej\\xe9rv\\xe1ry-Pulszky collection in Budapest, the fragments were said to be of ancient Roman origin. Working in support of that idea, someone did his best to destroy the inscription's contradictory evidence.", "classification": "Sculpture-Bronze", "accession_number": "2004.440.1", "geographic_location": "Europe,Italy,Venice", "object_type_material": "Bronze,Copper alloy,Fragments,Friezes,Metal,Sculpture"}

Pierpont Morgan, 1917", "description": "The consummate skill of goldsmiths in Nasrid Granada is evident in these necklace elements, which combine filigree, granulation, and cloisonn\\xe9 enamelwork. The Latin inscription on the central pendant, \"Hail Mary, full of Grace,\" the salutation of the archangel Gabriel when he revealed to the Virgin Mary that she would give birth to the Christ Child, leaves no doubt that this necklace excavated in Granada before 1916 was meant to be worn by a Christian. Among a series of exceptional works that have been attributed to the same Nasrid workshop are items that were clearly destined for Muslim, Christian, and Jewish patrons.", "classification": "Metalwork-Gold", "accession_number": "17.190.161a-j", "geographic_location": "Andalusia,Europe,Granada,Spain", "object_type_material": "Costume,Enamels,Gold,Jewelry,Metal,Metalwork,Necklaces"}

column23: {"image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ep/web-large/DT206354.jpg", "title": "Saint Teresa of \\xc1vila Interceding for Souls in Purgatory", "artist": "Workshop of Peter Paul Rubens (Flemish, Siegen 1577\\u20131640 Antwerp)", "medium": "Oil on wood", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/437542", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "dimensions": "25 1/4 x 19 1/4 in. (64.1 x 48.9 cm)", "credit_line": "Gift of J. Pierpont Morgan, 1917", "description": "The present painting is a reduced workshop version of a large altarpiece painted by Rubens about 1630 to 1633 for the Church of the Discalced Carmelites in Antwerp. The inscription on an engraving by Schelte a Bolswert after Rubens's altarpiece relates the scene to the story of Bernardino de Mendoza, a young Spaniard who had given Saint Teresa land on which to build a convent. Bernardino died before it could be built, and Christ appeared to Saint Teresa informing her that his soul could not be released from Purgatory until the convent was completed. Bernardino appears in Purgatory at the left of the painting.", "classification": "Paintings", "accession_number": "17.190.19", "geographic_location": "Europe,Flanders", "artist_maker_culture": "Peter Paul Rubens", "object_type_material": "Oil paint,Paintings"}
