column19: Manuscript Illumination with the Evangelist Luke
column23: {"date": "late 13th\\u2013early 14th century", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/md/web-large/DT5330.jpg", "title": "Manuscript Illumination with the Evangelist Luke", "medium": "Tempera and gold on parchment", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/473633", "culture": "Byzantine", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1000\\u20131400", "dimensions": "5 13/16 x 4 1/16 in.  (14.7 x 10.3 cm)", "credit_line": "Purchase, The Jaharis Family Foundation Inc. Gift, 2001", "description": "On a single page from a gospel book, the illumination shows the evangelist Luke seated on a backless chair, reaching with his left arm toward the open book on a pedestal before him. He wears a loose-fitting blue tunic and white himation, and sandals on his feet. He holds a quill pen in his right hand as he pauses to contemplate the text. His sandaled feet rest on a footstool, next to a small book cabinet that extends beyond the border of the illumination. Careful study of the cabinet reveals the artist's attention to detail, for there neatly arranged are all of Luke's writing implements, including his inkwell and a knife for sharpening his quills. The sparse furnishings in the scene\\u2014pedestal, chair, footstool, and cabinet\\u2014are all carefully painted in tan and oak shades with white highlighting and texturing. A gold ground provides the only backdrop for the seated figure, framed by a simple ochre and red border. The short inscription at the top is the Greek o hag[ios] Loukas (Saint Luke). The other side of the leaf was left blank. This was often the case in the Late Byzantine period, when it was common practice to execute the illuminations for a codex separately and tip them into the pages of text afterward. The blank side is thus the leaf's recto, so that the illumination could face the opening text of Luke's gospel.", "classification": "Manuscripts and Illuminations", "accession_number": "2001.633", "object_type_material": "Gold,Illuminations,Lighting,Manuscripts,Metal,Paintings,Parchment,Tempera"}

{"date": "16th century", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/es/web-large/sf91-1-137a.jpg", "title": "Dish", "medium": "Tin-glazed and luster-painted earthenware", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/187252", "culture": "Spanish, Valencia", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1400\\u20131600", "dimensions": "Diameter: 19 in. (48.3 cm)", "credit_line": "Edward C. Moore Collection, Bequest of Edward C. Moore, 1891", "description": "Tin-glazed earthenware, of which lusterware is one type, was developed in the Middle East in the ninth and tenth centuries to imitate the porcelains produced in China. The opaque white glaze concealed the clay body, which could range from pale buff to brick red, allowing for brilliant effects created by painting the white surface with metal oxides that fired to a range of colors. This technique, as well as the use of metallic luster\\u2014an iridescent, coppery painted glaze\\u2014spread throughout the Muslim world, arriving among the potters of Valencia in the thirteenth century. The so-called Hispano-Moresque lusterware, with its fusion of Islamic and Gothic styles and motifs, often in shaped imitating those of metal vessels, was treasured by the elite in Spain during the fifteenth century and exported to the courts of Europe. The Valencian industry declined in the late sixteenth century, as colorful Italian Renaissance maiolica gained in popularity among the fashionable and as Spanish centers were founded to produce versions of its pictorial forms. {"date": "1462", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/md/web-large/DP228487.jpg", "title": "Chalice", "medium": "Gilded silver, filigree enamel, pearls", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/478973", "culture": "Southeastern European", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1400\\u20131600", "dimensions": "Overall: 8 7/16 x 5 1/2 in. (21.5 x 14 cm)\\r\\ndiam. of cup: 4 3/16 in. (10.6 cm)", "credit_line": "Gift of The Salgo Trust for Education, New York, in memory of Nicolas M. Salgo, 2010", "description": "High-ranking church officials would have used this flamboyant Gothic chalice on special occasions, and the object\\u2019s colorful and glittering appearance would have been in divine harmony with the multicolored sunlight coming through the stained glass windows. The grandeur of the delicate filigree enameling became associated with the term modo transilvano, or, \\u201cin the Transylvanian fashion.\\u201d Along with bejeweled examples, ostentatiously colorful, enameled chalices, such as this one, were the pride of church treasuries in Central and Southeastern Europe and Northern Italy, including Venice, which had a common border with the fifteenth-century Hungarian Kingdom. The majority of ecclesiastical silver was destroyed during the Reformation in the sixteenth- century. The chalice bears the date 1462 and names the otherwise unknown donor Nicolas Cynowec. The object itself is equally illustrious as its distinguished provenance, from the collection of Baron Nathaniel de Rothschild in Vienna.", "classification": "Metalwork-Silver", "accession_number": "2010.109.6", "object_type_material": "Chalices,Enamels,Filigree,Gilt,Metal,Metalwork,Pearl,Silver"}

{"_": "Attributed to the Baltimore Painter", "date": "ca. 330\\u2013310 B.C.", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/gr/web-large/DP140114.jpg", "title": "Terracotta volute-krater (mixing bowl)", "medium": "Terracotta; red-figure", "period": "Late Classical", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/255282", "culture": "Greek, South Italian, Apulian", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "1000 B.C.\\u2013A.D. 1", "dimensions": "H. with handles 30 5/16 in. (77 cm); H. to rim  26 3/4 in. (68 cm)", "credit_line": "Purchase, Mrs. James J. Rorimer Gift, 1969", "description": "Obverse:  the Judgment of Paris. The Trojan prince is seated in the center, dressed in Eastern garb. He listens to Hermes, standing to his right, who has brought the three goddesses to him to be judged. Aphrodite, accompanied by Eros is in the upper left, seated beside a large box, holding a wreath and a mirror. Hera, holding her scepter is seated in the upper right on a rock. Athena, directly below Paris, is also seated, leaning  on her shield, wearing her helmet and holding a large phiale. Athena is attended by two youths, who, like Paris, are in Eastern costume. In the same register, at the extreme left, a young Pan, leaning on a rock, observes the scene. On the neck: frontal head of a woman wearing a Phrygian cap emerging from a blossom, surrounded by flowers and tendrils. On the handles, in relief, heads of Io with blonde hair.  Reverse: naiskos with a statue of the deceased woman holding a wreath, a long sash, and a flower. Around the naiskos four mourners. Above, on either side is a seated youth holding a box; the one on the left also  holds grapes. The other, a situla. column17: Julia Margaret Cameron (British (born India), Calcutta 1815–1879 Kalutara, Ceylon)
column23: {"date": "April 1867", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ph/web-large/DT2539.jpg", "title": "Sir John Herschel", "artist": "Julia Margaret Cameron (British (born India), Calcutta 1815\\u20131879 Kalutara, Ceylon)", "medium": "Albumen silver print from glass negative", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/283097", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1800\\u20131900", "dimensions": "Image: 31.8 x 24.9 cm (12 1/2 x 9 13/16 in.)Mount: 39.9 x 32.9 cm (15 11/16 x 12 15/16 in.), corners clipped", "credit_line": "Gilman Collection, Purchase, Robert Rosenkranz Gift, 2005", "description": "Sir John Herschel (1792\\u20131871) was Victorian England\\u2019s preeminent scientist, astronomer, and mathematician, considered the equal of Sir Isaac Newton. Cameron met him in 1836 in Capetown, South Africa, where she was recuperating from illness and he was charting the stars of the southern hemisphere and recording the native flora. Just a few years later Herschel wrote to her in Calcutta of Henry Talbot\\u2019s invention of photography and sent her the first photographs she had ever seen\\u2014scientific discoveries that were \\u201cwater to the parched lips of the starved,\\u201d she recalled. Of her 1867 portraits of Herschel, she wrote: \\u201cFrom my earliest girlhood I had loved and honoured him, and it was after a friendship of 31 years\\u2019 duration that the high task of giving his portrait to the nation was allotted to me,\\u201d sounding a bit as though she were working on a divine commission rather than on a personal, spiritual, artistic quest\\u2014with, it must be said, some incidental hope of financial profit. Of the four exposures Cameron made in April 1867, Herschel preferred this one, which portrayed him, he thought, as an \\u201cold Paterfamilias.\\u201d", "classification": "Photographs", "accession_number": "2005.100.25", "geographic_location": "Europe,United Kingdom", "artist_maker_culture": "Julia Margaret Cameron", "object_type_material": "Albumen silver prints,Photographs"}

column23: {"date": "second half 16th century", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/es/web-large/LC-32_100_376-001.jpg", "maker": "Probably by Vincenzo di Marco", "title": "Albarello", "medium": "Maiolica (tin-glazed earthenware)", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/197224", "culture": "Italian, Sicily or Faenza", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1400\\u20131600", "dimensions": "Overall (confirmed): 7 3/8 \\xd7 5 1/16 in. (18.7 \\xd7 12.9 cm)", "credit_line": "The Friedsam Collection, Bequest of Michael Friedsam, 1931", "description": "Storage vessels were among the most frequently produced maiolica wares in late medieval and Renaissance Italy. Made in fairly standard shapes, they were designed to fit with dozens of others on a shelf, often in a pharmacy or shop. Their handles therefore tend to fit within the vessel\\u2019s profile, and the cylindrical albarello type is generally narrower at the middle than at the top or bottom, making it easy to grip. Other common features include inscriptions indicating contents and flanged lips to help secure cloth or paper seals. The decoration, usually more elaborate on one side than the other, can sometimes link pieces to a known dispensary or specific workshop or artist.", "classification": "Ceramics-Pottery", "accession_number": "32.100.376", "geographic_location": "Europe,Italy,Sicily", "artist_maker_culture": "Vincenzo di Marco", "object_type_material": "Albarelli,Apothecary jars,Ceramics,Earthenware,Glazing,Maiolica,Pottery"}

(37.5 x 27 cm)", "translator": "Henry Francis Cary (British (parents Irish), Gibraltar 1772\\u20131844 London)", "credit_line": "Rogers Fund, 1905, transferred from the Library, 1921", "description": "Out of his facility for grotesque humor and gaslight melodrama, Dor\\xe9; invented some 10,000 illustrations for books and magazines that were duplicated for simultaneous publications in Paris, Berlin, Barcelona, Saint Petersburg, Stockholm, London, and Haarlem. column19: Page of Calligraphy from a Mantiq al-tair (Language of the Birds)
column23: {"date": "ca. 1600", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/is/web-large/sf63-210-21r.jpg", "title": "Page of Calligraphy from a Mantiq al-tair (Language of the Birds)", "author": "Farid al-Din `Attar (ca. 1142\\u20131220)", "medium": "Ink, opaque watercolor, gold, and silver on paper", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/451727", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "geography": "Made in Iran", "credit_line": "Fletcher Fund, 1963", "description": "This folio belonged to a manuscript of the Mantiq al-Tair that was presented to the Ardabil shrine in 1608\\u201309, more than a century after its text and most of its illustrations were completed.  Under the Safavid Shah \\u2018Abbas, its pages were remounted and four illustrations, a frontispiece, and a new binding were added.  For a long time, the text and paintings were assumed to be Timurid, from the original manuscript.  Scholars have determined, however, that this folio is one of fifteen Safavid additions that were produced to replace damaged or lost folios.  The original calligrapher of the manuscript was Sultan \\u2018Ali Mashhadi, a famed calligrapher and poet of the late fifteenth and early sixteenth centuries.", "object_name": "Folio from an illustrated manuscript", "classification": "Codices", "accession_number": "63.210.21", "geographic_location": "Asia,Iran", "artist_maker_culture": "Farid al-Din `Attar", "object_type_material": "Codices,Folios,Gold,Illuminated manuscripts,Ink,Manuscripts,Metal,Paper,Silver,Watercolors"}

column17: Mathew B. Brady (American, born Ireland, 1823?–1896 New York)
column23: {"date": "1865", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ph/web-large/DP248323.jpg", "title": "General Robert E. Lee", "artist": "Mathew B. Brady (American, born Ireland, 1823?\\u20131896 New York)", "medium": "Albumen silver print from glass negative", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/286582", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1800\\u20131900", "dimensions": "Image: 14 \\xd7 9.3 cm (5 1/2 \\xd7 3 11/16 in.)", "credit_line": "Gilman Collection, Museum Purchase, 2005", "description": "Confederate General Robert E. Lee surrendered his army to Union General Ulysses S. Grant at Appomattox Court House, Virginia, on April 9, 1865. The Civil War was over. If not whole, the nation was at least reunited, and the slow recovery of Reconstruction could begin. As soon as he heard that Lee had left Appomattox and returned to Richmond, Mathew B. Brady headed there with his camera equipment. The Lees\\u2019 Franklin Street residence had survived the fires that had devastated many of the commercial sections of the city. Through the kindness of Mrs. Lee and a Confederate colonel, Brady received permission to photograph the general on April 16, 1865, just two days after President Lincoln\\u2019s assassination. Brady\\u2019s portrait of General Lee holding his hat, on his own back porch, is one of the most reflective and thoughtful wartime likenesses. The fifty-eight-year-old Confederate hero poses in the uniform he had worn at the surrender. It would be Brady\\u2019s last wartime photograph.", "classification": "Photographs", "accession_number": "2005.100.1213", "geographic_location": "North and Central America,United States", "artist_maker_culture": "Mathew . Brady", "object_type_material": "Albumen silver prints,Photographs"}

column19: Arcadian Landscape with Three Figures at a Lake
column23: {"date": "1792", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/dp/web-large/DP162181.jpg", "title": "Arcadian Landscape with Three Figures at a Lake", "artist": "Johann Christian Reinhart (German, Hof 1761\\u20131847 Rome)", "medium": "Black chalk, and white gouache on brown paper", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/377597", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1600\\u20131800", "dimensions": "sheet: 23 x 33 7/8 in. (58.4 x 86 cm)", "credit_line": "Rogers Fund, 2007", "description": "Reinhart made this imposing drawing in Rome in 1792, when he and another leading German artist from the period, Joseph Anton Koch, started making \"heroic\" or \"poetic\" landscapes inspired as much by the Roman campagna as by the work of their seventeenth-century predecessors Claude Lorrain, Nicolas Poussin, and Gaspard Dughet. Although the figures are dressed in a style that hints at a specific mythological or historical subject, they were probably used merely to indicate the antique setting of the landscape, as were the villa in the left background and the funerary monuments at center and in the right background. The dense composition and regular hatching are typical of Reinhart's manner throughout his career. The drawing is related to a painting he made in 1796 (Museum Georg Sch\\xe4fer, Schweinfurt), but it cannot be called preparatory, for it differs from the painting in many ways. Fully signed and dated, and preserved in what is likely to be its original frame, the drawing was made as an independent work of art.", "classification": "Drawings", "accession_number": "2007.264", "geographic_location": "Europe,Germany", "artist_maker_culture": "Johann Christian Reinhart", "object_type_material": "Chalk,Drawings,Gouache,Paper,Watercolors"}

{"date": "15th\\u201316th century", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/cl/web-large/cdi55-61-12.jpg", "title": "Lock", "medium": "Iron", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/471589", "culture": "European", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1400\\u20131600", "dimensions": "Overall: 6 3/4 x 9 in. (17.1 x 22.9 cm)", "credit_line": "The Cloisters Collection, 1955", "description": "The decoration of Gothic iron locks and keys was often elaborate and of the highest standard of workmanship. The motifs were frequently drawn from Gothic architecture, reproducing on a miniature scale complicated tracery patterns and even tiny statuettes. A number of these tiny locks were compound, with some of the mechanisms concealed from view, and required two or even three keys used in sequence to open them. It has been suggested that the greatly expanded use of locks on doors, or coffrets and other types of storage chests was a result of the increasing urbanization of life and the new emphasis on material wealth and private ownership which developed in the late Middle Ages.", "classification": "Metalwork-Iron", "accession_number": "55.61.12", "geographic_location": "Europe", "object_type_material": "Iron,Iron and iron alloy,Locks,Metal,Metalwork"}

{"date": "ca. 1802\\u20131550 B.C.", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/eg/web-large/33.1.91_EGDP019381.jpg", "title": "Magical Figure", "medium": "Clay (unfired)", "period": "Late Middle Kingdom\\u2013Second Intermediate Period", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/546374", "dynasty": "Dynasty 13\\u2013SIP", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "2000\\u20131000 B.C.", "geography": "From Egypt, Memphite Region, Lisht South, west of mastaba of Senwosretankh, surface deposit, MMA excavations, 1932\\u201333", "dimensions": "H. 6.3 cm (2 1/2 in.); W. 3.3 cm (1 5/16 in.)", "credit_line": "Rogers Fund, 1933", "description": "These  tablets of unfired clay with attached crude faces were found as a group by the Museum's excavators at Lisht South in loose surface sand west of the mastaba of  Senwosretankh, a high official and possibly the architect of the pyramid complex of Senwosret I (ca. 1961\\u20131917 B. C.), east of which he erected his own very elaborate mastaba tomb (see acc. nos. 33.1.2 and other pieces).  The mud figures and little coffin (acc. no. 33.1.66) that had contained some of them must have been buried, however, considerably later than the early twelfth dynasty tomb close to which they were found.  In fact, during the thirteenth and following dynasties people deposited a number of objects in the by then sacred area around a legendary ruler's pyramid and its dependant monuments, believing conceivably that potent magical powers could thus be released. These flat mud figures, for instance, are inscribed in now much-faded red paint with the names of men identified as enemies (most of them Egyptians but some with foreign names).  Their deposition may have been thought to effect their destruction.", "accession_number": "33.1.91", "geographic_location": "Africa,Al Lisht,Egypt,Mersa Matr\\xfbh", "object_type_material": "Clay,Figures,Tablets"}

column23: {"date": "1766", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/dp/web-large/DP808883.jpg", "title": "The Repeal, or the Funeral of Miss Ame-Stamp", "artist": "Anonymous, British, 18th century", "medium": "Hand-colored etching", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/388969", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1600\\u20131800", "publisher": "Carington Bowles I (British, 1724\\u20131793)", "dimensions": "plate: 8 7/8 x 13 5/8 in. (22.5 x 34.6 cm)\\r\\nsheet: 11 1/8 x 14 7/8 in. (28.3 x 37.8 cm)", "credit_line": "Gift of Walter L. Hildberg, 1923", "description": "British politicians are imagined processing through the London docks to mourn the repeal of the Stamp Act on March 18, 1766. A year before, Parliament had imposed this excise tax on printed goods imported to the American colonies. Resulting boycotts led British merchants to pressure the government for repeal, and this anti-tax image mocks the act\\u2019s leading supporters. Behind two flag bearers, George Grenville (dismissed as chief minister in 1765) carries a small coffin marked \"Miss Ame[rica] Stamp.\" He is followed by Lord Bute, another former chief minister identified by his Scottish bonnet and tartan suit. The London publisher Carington Bowles borrowed the composition from a print issued by a rival that sold thousands of copies. It uses the language of political satire Romeyn de Hooghe developed in Holland, combined with a simple dramatic structure that makes the elaborate allegory easy to understand.", "published_in": "London", "classification": "Prints", "accession_number": "23.42", "geographic_location": "England,Europe,London,United Kingdom", "artist_maker_culture": "Anonymous, British, 18th century,Carington Bowles I", "object_type_material": "Etching,Prints"}

{"date": "1880", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ci/web-large/56.67_front_CP4.jpg", "title": "Dinner dress", "medium": "silk, metal", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/159377", "culture": "Spanish", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1800\\u20131900", "credit_line": "Brooklyn Museum Costume Collection at The Metropolitan Museum of Art, Gift of the Brooklyn Museum, 2009; Gift of Laura Bustamante, 1956", "description": "The bustle silhouette, although primarily associated with the second half of the 19th century, originated in earlier fashions as a simple bump at the back of the dress, such as with late 17th-early 18th century mantuas and late 18th- early 19th century Empire dresses.  The full-blown bustle silhouette had its first Victorian appearance in the late 1860s, which started as fullness in skirts moving to the back of the dress.  This fullness was drawn up in ties for walking that created a fashionable puff.  This trendsetting puff expanded and was then built up with supports from a variety of different things such as horsehair, metal hoops and down.  Styles of this period were often taken from historical inspiration and covered in various types of trim and lace.  Accessories were petite and allowed for the focus on the large elaborate gowns.  Around 1874, the style altered and the skirts began to hug the thighs in the front while the bustle at the back was reduced to a natural flow from the waist to the train.  This period was marked by darker colors, asymmetrical drapery, oversize accessories and elongated forms created by full-length coats.  Near the beginning of the 1880s the trends altered once again to include the bustle, this time it would reach its maximum potential with some skirts having the appearance of a full shelf at the back.  The dense textiles preferred were covered in trimming, beadwork, puffs and bows to visually elevate them further.  The feminine silhouette continued like this through 1889 before the skirts began to reduce and make way for the S-curve silhouette.", "accession_number": "2009.300.806", "geographic_location": "Europe,United Kingdom", "object_type_material": "Costume,Dresses,Metal,Silk"}

column19: A Woman Cleaning, Plate 5 from Five Feminine Occupations
column23: {"date": "ca. 1648\\u201350", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/dp/web-large/MM43416.jpg", "title": "A Woman Cleaning, Plate 5 from Five Feminine Occupations", "artist": "Geertruydt Roghman (Dutch, Amsterdam 1625\\u20131651/57 Amsterdam (?))", "medium": "Engraving", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/383483", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1600\\u20131800", "dimensions": "Plate: 8 7/16 \\xd7 6 11/16 in. (21.5 \\xd7 17 cm)\\r\\nSheet: 11 7/16 \\xd7 8 5/16 in. (29.1 \\xd7 21.1 cm)", "credit_line": "The Elisha Whittelsey Collection, The Elisha Whittelsey Fund, 1956", "description": "Roghman, from an Amsterdam family of artists, is known for some reproductive prints and her original suite of five engravings, \"Household Tasks\": sewing, spinning, reading (?), cooking, and cleaning cookware (see 56.500.2\\u2013.6). The two subjects set in kitchens are unusual in that the solitary maids are seen from behind. Each print presents a sober view of domestic work, but the kitchen scenes are remarkable for the figures' complete lack of individuality, to say nothing of appeal. In comparing Roghman's images of household servants with those of Dou and Vermeer, it is tempting to distinguish male and female points of view (as some critics have rather emphatically). Whatever the interpretation, it is important to bear in mind that Roghman's prints were intended for a broad art market, whereas Dou's famously expensive paintings (as opposed to the later prints after them) and The Milkmaid by Vermeer were made with individual collectors in mind.", "classification": "Prints", "accession_number": "56.550.6", "geographic_location": "Europe,Netherlands", "artist_maker_culture": "Geertruydt Roghman", "object_type_material": "Engraving,Prints"}

{"date": "ca. 1616\\u201317", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ep/web-large/DP145901.jpg", "title": "Merrymakers at Shrovetide", "artist": "Frans Hals (Dutch, Antwerp 1582/83\\u20131666 Haarlem)", "medium": "Oil on canvas", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/436622", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1600\\u20131800", "dimensions": "51 3/4 x 39 1/4 in. (131.4 x 99.7 cm)", "credit_line": "Bequest of Benjamin Altman, 1913", "description": "The loud style of this early work by Hals suits its subject, which is Vastenavond (Shrovetide or Mardi Gras), a pre-Lenten carnival featuring bad food and worse behavior. Two characters from the comic stage, Peeckelhaering (Pickled Herring) and Hans Wurst (John Wiener?), cozy up to a young \"lady\" with a Dutch boy haircut and a bull neck. Hans's gesture, the deflated bagpipe, and other motifs comprise a chorus of sexual commentary. The picture looks surprisingly Flemish in its vivid coloring, loose brushwork, and crowded composition, which suggests that it may date from slightly after Hals's three months in Antwerp during 1616. In that mecca for Netherlandish artists he could have seen great works by Rubens and the early paintings of his own Flemish counterpart, Jacob Jordaens (1593\\u20131678).", "classification": "Paintings", "accession_number": "14.40.605", "geographic_location": "Europe,Netherlands", "artist_maker_culture": "Frans Hals", "object_type_material": "Canvas,Oil paint,Paintings"}

column17: Jean Antoine Houdon (French, Versailles 1741–1828 Paris), French, Paris
column23: {"date": "1788", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/es/web-large/DP242660.jpg", "title": "Sabine Houdon (1787\\u20131836)", "artist": "Jean Antoine Houdon (French, Versailles 1741\\u20131828 Paris)", "medium": "White marble on gray marble socle", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/200668", "culture": "French, Paris", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1600\\u20131800", "dimensions": "Overall, without base (confirmed): H. 10 3/4 x W. 8 7/8 x D. 5 7/8 in., 20lb. (27.3 x 22.5 x 14.9 cm, 9.0719kg); Height with base (confirmed): 13 1/2 in. (34.3 cm)", "credit_line": "Bequest of Mary Stillman Harkness, 1950", "description": "Among all of Houdon's beloved depictions of children, the most beautiful may be the head of his own daughter Sabine, portrayed at the age of ten months. The fashionable Enlightenment interest in innocence and childhood created a vogue for children's busts, which Houdon produced in quantity (including several of his three daughters at various ages). But images of babies this young are rare and, aside from the plaster model in the Louvre, no other versions of this model are known. The marble has been most lovingly worked\\u2014the delicate naturalistic folds of flesh at the intersection of Sabine's chest and arms are carved with a melting softness that perfectly captures the limpid fragility of infant skin. Her alert gaze and unsentimentaliized features present a personality whose distinction transcends the category.", "classification": "Sculpture", "accession_number": "50.145.66", "geographic_location": "Europe,France,Paris", "artist_maker_culture": "Jean Antoine Houdon", "object_type_material": "Busts,Figures,Marble,Sculpture"}

{"date": "6th\\u20139th century", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ao/web-large/DP270994.jpg", "title": "Prisoner Lime Container", "medium": "Wood, bone inlay, paint", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/310308", "culture": "Wari", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 500\\u20131000", "geography": "Peru", "dimensions": "H. 3  x  W. 1 1/2 x  D. 1 5/16 in. (7.6 x 3.8 x 3.3 cm)", "credit_line": "Purchase, Rogers Fund and Carol R. Meyer and Arthur M. Bullowa Gifts, 1977", "description": "This small wood sculpture is a container that in ancient times would have held powdered lime made from calcined seashells. The lime would have been taken from the container through the hole in the top by means of a little spatuala or spoon. Lime was a necessary part of the ritual of coca-leaf chewing; the coca leaves were put into the mouth to form a quid, and then the lime was added.        Ancient lime containers are known in a variety of different forms and materials, and among them those of Huari-Tiahuanaco times of about the eighth or ninth century are of particular interest. Often sculptural in form and made of wood, they can be rather elaborately conceived for such small works. This figure, wearing a checkerboard shirt and a feline's-head helmet, also has designs painted on his cheeks, a short, broad nose ornament and hands \"tied\" behind his back by a still present \"rope\" or cord. The bone inlay in the stomach adds richness to an already quite richly ornamented figure. Why a lime container would be made in the form of a bound figure is presently unclear. The container is allegedly from the site of Cahuachi in the Nazca Valley.", "classification": "Wood-Containers", "accession_number": "1977.376", "geographic_location": "Peru,South America", "artist_maker_culture": "Wari", "object_type_material": "Bone,Lime"}

column17: Pieter Bruegel the Elder (Netherlandish, Breda (?) ca. 1525–1569 Brussels),  Frans Huys (Netherlandish, 1522–1562), Hieronymus Cock (Netherlandish, Antwerp ca. 1510–1570 Antwerp)
column19: Four-master and Two Three-masters Anchored near a Fortified Island from The Sailing Vessels
column23: {"date": "1561\\u201365", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/dp/web-large/DP818244.jpg", "title": "Four-master and Two Three-masters Anchored near a Fortified Island from The Sailing Vessels", "artist": " Frans Huys (Netherlandish, 1522\\u20131562)", "medium": "Engraving and etching; first state of three", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/338712", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1400\\u20131600", "publisher": "Hieronymus Cock (Netherlandish, Antwerp ca. 1510\\u20131570 Antwerp)", "dimensions": "Plate: 8 7/8 \\xd7 11 9/16 in. (22.5 \\xd7 29.4 cm)\\r\\nSheet: 10 15/16 \\xd7 13 in. (27.8 \\xd7 33 cm)", "credit_line": "Bequest of Alexandrine Sinsheimer, 1959", "description": "This engraving belongs to a series of ten prints known as the Sailing Vessels, executed by Frans Huys after designs by Pieter Bruegel the Elder. The series displays a wide range of sailing vessels, including merchantmen and warships, large seagoing vessels and small coasters, galleys, and caravels. Here, Bruegel depicted a four-master, i.e., a ship with four masts, and two three-masters anchored near a fortified island capped by a lighthouse. The detail and painstaking accuracy with which the vessels are rendered attests to the artist's great care and leaves no doubt that Bruegel must have prepared for the series by making numerous sketches and elaborate studies\\u2014all of which unfortunately are lost. At what point in his life Bruegel became interested in the subject of ships is unclear, but the deep fascination the citizens of Antwerp took in it is understandable given the nature of the city's economy. As a mercantile superpower with direct access to the North Sea, and as home to some of the most ambitious traders and explorers in Europe, Antwerp took great pride in the prowess and engineering of their ships and in their connection to the sea. Whatever the precise source of their appeal, Bruegel's series of Sailing Vessels was a highly sophisticated creation that far surpassed previous examples of the genre in technique and imagination.", "classification": "Prints", "accession_number": "59.534.23", "geographic_location": "Europe,Netherlands", "artist_maker_culture": "Pieter Bruegel the Elder,Hieronymus Cock,Frans Huys", "object_type_material": "Engraving,Etching,Prints"}

(29.2 cm)", "credit_line": "The Cesnola Collection, Purchased by subscription, 1874\\u201376", "description": "The Cesnola Collection is fortunate to have two fine early heads that belonged to full-length figures. Large-scale terracotta sculpture began to be made on Cyprus during the mid-seventh century B.C. Molds were used for the heads, while the bodies were handmade. This bearded head wears the helmetlike headgear that appears on the nearby limestone sculptures. Details are articulated with considerable care, and remaining pigment suggests the liveliness of the figures' original appearance.", "classification": "Terracottas", "accession_number": "74.51.1458", "geographic_location": "Asia,Cyprus", "object_type_material": "Clay,Terracotta"}

{"date": "310\\u2013150 B.C.", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/gr/web-large/DP121930.jpg", "title": "Terracotta jug with a pitcher-spout", "medium": "Terracotta", "period": "Hellenistic", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/240131", "culture": "Cypriot", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "1000 B.C.\\u2013A.D. 1", "dimensions": "h. 9 1/2 in. (24.1 cm)", "credit_line": "The Cesnola Collection, Purchased by subscription, 1874\\u201376", "description": "This jug is a variation on a type of Cypriot vessel that has a figurine holding the oinochoe, which serves as its spout. Despite the absence of such a figure, which when present often helps to date jugs of this kind, the overall form of the pitcher identifies it as a product of the Hellenistic period. The wreaths and fillets painted on the white-slip ground are funerary motifs often seen on white ground lekythoi, vases specifically used as grave gifts. Of particular interest are the small clay \"rivets\" visible at the top of the back handle, which relates this clay jug to a metal prototype.", "classification": "Vases", "accession_number": "74.51.544", "geographic_location": "Asia,Cyprus", "object_type_material": "Clay,Jugs,Terracotta,Vases,Vessels"}

{"date": "ca. 1981\\u20131975 B.C.", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/eg/web-large/DP341852.jpg", "reign": "reign of Amenemhat I, early", "title": "Model Sporting Boat", "medium": "Plastered and painted wood, linen, linen twine, copper", "period": "Middle Kingdom", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/544126", "dynasty": "Dynasty 12", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "2000\\u20131000 B.C.", "geography": "From Egypt, Upper Egypt, Thebes, Southern Asasif, Tomb of Meketre (TT 280, MMA 1101), Serdab, MMA excavations, 1920", "dimensions": "Boat with rudder and paddles: L. 121.7 cm (47 15/16 in.); H. 34.3 cm (13 1/2 in.); W. 30.6 cm (12 1/16 in.)Hull: L. 112.5 cm (44 5/16 in.); W. 23.7 cm (9 5/16 in.)", "credit_line": "Rogers Fund and Edward S. Harkness Gift, 1920", "description": "Among the pleasures of an Egyptian noble's life were hunting excursions in the Nile marshes to fish and hunt birds. Papyrus rafts or light boats such as this were used for such excursions. Here, Meketre and his son or companion are watching the hunters from a light shelter made of woven reeds and decorated with two large shields. In the prow, two men aim harpoons at some fish, while amidships a kneeling fisherman removes the harpoon from a bolti fish. An earlier catch, a large Mormyrus, is being presented to Meketre. A bunchof coots, caught previously in a clapnet, are presented by a man and a woman, who wears a bead net over her shoulders, brings a duck. The poles of the clapnet are now lashed to the grilles of the shelter; the net pegs lie on the deck. The presence of females from a noble's family in such marsh scenes is a recurring theme in Egyptian art.", "accession_number": "20.3.6", "geographic_location": "Africa,Egypt,Thebes,Upper Egypt", "object_type_material": "Boats,Copper,Cord,Linen,Metal,Painting,Twine,Wood"}

column19: Model for the so-called "Female Saint of Starnberg"
column23: {"date": "ca. 1755", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/es/web-large/DP217096.jpg", "maker": "Ignaz G\\xfcnther (German, Altmannstein 1725\\u20131775 Munich)", "title": "Model for the so-called \"Female Saint of Starnberg\"", "medium": "Linden wood with pencil marks", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/236118", "culture": "German, Munich", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1600\\u20131800", "dimensions": "Overall (confirmed): H. 8 1/8 x W. 4 1/8 x D. 2 7/8 in. (20.6 x 10.5 x 7.3 cm)", "credit_line": "European Sculpture and Decorative Arts Fund, 2008", "description": "The celebrated eighteenth-century Munich court sculptor Ignaz G\\xfcnther carved this mesmerizing statuette. It is a \"bozetto,\" or working model, for the nearly lifesize sculpture of the so-called \"Female Saint of Starnberg,\" whose haunting composition was widely considered to be one of the artist's most innovative and poignant figural inventions. G\\xfcnther captured the principal forms and volumes and the essential elements of the composition in his 'bozetto\" in the same way a painter would use a sketch. Though the model's surface is still angular and the detailing is uneven, its elegance and courtly gesture presage its transformation into a large figure. The seductive twisting of the saint's body, her theatrically animated costume rippling in an imaginary breeze, and the play of light and shadow contrast dramatically with the aura of restrained ecstasy. Whimsical sculptural accents such as the coiffure reflect G\\xfcnther's superior command of the medium. He has transformed the wood material into a pr\\xe9cis of heavenly lightness more befitting a ballerina than a female saint. His naturalistic rendering reflects the spirit of South German Rococo at its very best.", "classification": "Sculpture", "accession_number": "2008.28", "geographic_location": "Bavaria,Europe,Germany,Munich", "artist_maker_culture": "Ignaz G\\xfcnther", "object_type_material": "Figurines,Pencil,Sculpture,Statues,Wood"}

(28.8 x 20.4 cm)", "credit_line": "Rogers Fund, 1967", "description": "This sheet contains two ideas for the decoration of a frame in which a satyr takes center stage. In the design on top a satyr mask is being crowned with a laurel wreath by two cherubs while in the lower design, a vase decorated with satyr masks is placed centrally on top of the frame and is flanked by the figures of two young satyrs. Because only a small part of the frame below is shown, it is hard to tell what kind of frame this was meant to be, although the heavy ornament on top suggest that it is most likely an architectural frame for a door or a window. The artist, Gregorio de\\u2019 Ferrari, is known to have made designs for the interior, most notably in the Palazzo Rosso along the prestigious Strada Nova in Genoa. He worked there together with Domenico Piola, for whose family workshop De\\u2019 Ferrari also designed tombs, altars, textiles, silver, ship decorations and frontispieces.", "classifications": "Drawings, Ornament & Architecture", "accession_number": "67.95.9", "geographic_location": "Europe,Italy", "artist_maker_culture": "Gregorio de' Ferrari", "object_type_material": "Chalk,Drawings,Ink"}

{"date": "second quarter 15th century", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/rl/web-large/sf-rlc-1975-1-330.JPG", "title": "A Warrior on Horseback", "artist": "The Veneto (1425\\u20131449)", "medium": "Pen and brown ink, brown wash, over black chalk", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/459412", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1400\\u20131600", "dimensions": "8 1/16 x 5 11/16 in.  (20.5 x 14.5 cm)", "credit_line": "Robert Lehman Collection, 1975", "description": "This study for a warrior on horseback has formerly been attributed to the Venetian artist, Michele Giambono, due to the general resemblance of the subject to the master\\u2019s fresco of the equestrian figure of San Crisogono (San Trovaso, Venice). However, given the differences of pose and style, the relationship is too generic to ascribe the two works to the same hand. It appears instead that both Giambono\\u2019s painted equestrian figure and this study were independently modeled on the same source: the ancient bronze horses of the Basilica of San Marco in Venice. The horse\\u2019s stance, with its raised front right leg, and head angled toward the right, as well as some anatomical details, recall the second horse from the left in the Venice group. The San Marco horses were a significant source of inspiration for equestrian imagery in the Renaissance, and artists who were not directly familiar with them may have known prototypes in the form of small statuettes.", "classification": "Drawings", "accession_number": "1975.1.330", "artist_maker_culture": "The Veneto", "object_type_material": "Black chalk,Chalk,Drawings,Ink,Pen"}

{"date": "16th century", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/es/web-large/SF94_4_360.jpg", "title": "Plateau", "medium": "Tin-glazed and luster-painted earthenware", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/187865", "culture": "Spanish, Valencia", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1400\\u20131600", "dimensions": "Diameter: 15 1/2 in. (39.4 cm)", "credit_line": "Gift of Henry G. Marquand, 1894", "description": "Tin-glazed earthenware, of which lusterware is one type, was developed in the Middle East in the ninth and tenth centuries to imitate the porcelains produced in China. The opaque white glaze concealed the clay body, which could range from pale buff to brick red, allowing for brilliant effects created by painting the white surface with metal oxides that fired to a range of colors. This technique, as well as the use of metallic luster\\u2014an iridescent, coppery painted glaze\\u2014spread throughout the Muslim world, arriving among the potters of Valencia in the thirteenth century. The so-called Hispano-Moresque lusterware, with its fusion of Islamic and Gothic styles and motifs, often in shaped imitating those of metal vessels, was treasured by the elite in Spain during the fifteenth century and exported to the courts of Europe. The Valencian industry declined in the late sixteenth century, as colorful Italian Renaissance maiolica gained in popularity among the fashionable and as Spanish centers were founded to produce versions of its pictorial forms. Adding to this decline was the expulsion from Valencia in 1609 of all the remaining Moriscos (Muslims converted to Christianity), though Christian potters reestablished the industry shortly thereafter.", "classification": "Ceramics-Pottery", "accession_number": "94.4.360", "geographic_location": "Europe,Spain,Valencia", "object_type_material": "Ceramics,Earthenware,Glazing,Luster,Painting,Plateaus,Pottery"}

{"date": "1769\\u201371", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/es/web-large/DP228589.jpg", "title": "Tureen and stand", "medium": "Silver, silver gilt", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/236747", "culture": "German, Augsburg", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1600\\u20131800", "goldsmith": "Bernhard Heinrich Weyhe (German, 1702\\u20131782)", "dimensions": "Tureen Overall (confirmed): 10 3/4 x 18 x 8 3/8 in.  (27.3 x 45.7 x 21.3 cm); Stand Overall (confirmed): 21 x 12 5/8 in. (53.3 x 32.1 cm); Overall weight (non-confirmed): 8.5 lbs. (3850 g)", "credit_line": "Wrightsman Fund, 2009", "description": "A pr\\xe9cis of how the precious metal silver could be transformed into a superior work of art by an artistic and imaginative mind, this tureen is a product of eighteenth-century Augsburg, undisputedly the foremost center of gold- and silversmithing in central Europe at the time. The sophisticated play of textures, daring juxtaposition of plain and lightcatching areas with detailed Rococo decoration, and whimsical sculptural elements reflect the commanding originality of the Augsburg artisans, particularly Bernhard Heinrich Weyhe, the maker of this piece and the leading Augsburg master. The touch of exotic chinoiserie in the pagoda-shaped outline of the tureen\\u2019s lid, so en vogue at the time, exemplifies Weyhe\\u2019s contributions to the Rococo style, which helped to define its interpretation in southern Germany. His creations are also famous for their highly sculptural finials. On this one, an elegant young woman in hunting costume holds a hooded falcon as a fox howls in the background. Falconry was one of the rare hunting sports that feudal ladies were allowed to participate in. The fox may allude to the contents of the game stew that would have been served in the tureen at hunting banquets, which at the time were lavish court rituals.", "classification": "Metalwork-Silver", "accession_number": "2009.263a\\u2013c", "geographic_location": "Augsburg,Bavaria,Europe,Germany", "artist_maker_culture": "Bernhard Heinrich Weyhe", "object_type_material": "Furniture,Gilt,Metal,Metalwork,Silver,Stands,Tureens"}

Kress Foundation, 1958", "description": "This small eating and work table mounted with S\\xe8vres porcelain plaques comes from the Hillingdon Collection, which was founded by Sir Charles Mills (1792\\u20131880), a partner in the great firm of Glyn, Mills, Currie and Company, bankers to the British royal family. Tradition says that Sir Charles acquired the collection during a series of visits to France in the first half of the nineteenth century. Sir Charles\\u2019 son was created first Baron Hillingdon in 1886. In 1937, his descendants sold the collection to the well-known art dealers Duveen Brothers. Although various collectors, such as Calouste Gulbenkian and J. Paul Getty, were interested in buying the Hillingdon Collection, ultimately the majority of the artworks, including seventeen pieces of porcelain-mounted furniture, were acquired in 1947 by the cultural foundation that had been established by the American businessman and philanthropist Samuel H. Kress (1863\\u20131955). Under the leadership of Samuel\\u2019s brother Rush H. Kress (1877\\u20131963), the Samuel H. Kress Foundation gave these extraordinary objects to the Museum in 1958, making it the foremost repository in the world of S\\xe8vres-mounted furniture.", "classification": "Woodwork-Furniture", "accession_number": "58.75.45", "geographic_location": "Europe,France,Paris", "artist_maker_culture": "Bernard III van Risamburgh,Bernard II van Risenburgh,S\\xe8vres Manufactory", "object_type_material": "Bronze,Clay,Copper alloy,Furniture,Gilt,Glass,Glass paste,Lacquer,Metal,Oak,Ormolu,Plate,Porcelain,Tables,Vernis Martin,Wood,Woodwork"}

(186.7 x 44.5 x 34.3 cm, 17690.3g)", "credit_line": "The Cloisters Collection, 1925", "description": "The bishop's chasuble, the principal vestment worn by a priest, is represented with a black orphrey ornamented with a series of quatrefoils. The top medallion shows Christ with his hand raised in benediction, while the others contain letters that spell AVE MARIA. The grandeur and nobility of this figure, a rare example of Gothic wood sculpture from Italy, results from the careful balance of the elements of the bishop's vestments\\u2014the tall miter and the long elliptical drapery folds\\u2014with the attenuated proportions, the frontality of the pose, the authority of the facial expression, and the refinement in the painted surfaces, especially on the face and beard.", "classification": "Sculpture-Wood", "accession_number": "25.120.218", "geographic_location": "Europe,Italy,Umbrian", "object_type_material": "Gilt,Poplar,Reliefs,Sculpture,Statues,Wood"}

{"date": "11th\\u201316th century", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ao/web-large/vs1991_419_32.jpg", "title": "Bird Spatula", "medium": "Gold", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/316692", "culture": "Popayan", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "geography": "Colombia", "dimensions": "H. 5 3/8 x W. 1 7/8 in. (13.7 x 4.8 cm)", "credit_line": "Jan Mitchell and Sons Collection, Gift of Jan Mitchell, 1991", "description": "The area near the town of Popay\\xe1n in the upper Cauca River area of Colombia has produced a number of handsome gold objects that are not related to any other styles. Of considerable visual appeal and superior craftsmanship, the elegant works are invariably cast of tumbaga; their surfaces were enriched by the depletion gilding method, also known as mise-en-couleur. Bird imagery is pervasive in the goldwork of Precolumbian America. Isthmian eagle pendants, with their characteristic frontal pose, are particularly well known, and different versions of the spread-wing-and-tail type come from Colombia as well. Here the artist has found an innovative way to depict the bird in full flight. Visualized from above, the bird appears to dive, its spread tail and wings forming a linear openwork pattern, perhaps to indicate feathers and to convey a sense of lightness. The bird's head, atop a strongly curved neck, has a fanned-out crest and strong beak that recalls a parrot. The bird adorns the top of a lime spatula that has an unusually short shaft. Spatulas were used to take powdered lime from a container and to add it to coca leaves for chewing. Coca chewing is a very ancient tradition in Andean South America and the paraphernalia for it could be elaborate and precious.", "classification": "Metal-Ornaments", "accession_number": "1991.419.32", "geographic_location": "Colombia,South America", "object_type_material": "Gold,Metal,Spatulas"}

{"date": "1787", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ep/web-large/DP-13139-001.jpg", "title": "The Death of Socrates", "artist": "Jacques Louis David (French, Paris 1748\\u20131825 Brussels)", "medium": "Oil on canvas", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/436105", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1600\\u20131800", "dimensions": "51 x 77 1/4 in. (129.5 x 196.2 cm)", "credit_line": "Catharine Lorillard Wolfe Collection, Wolfe Fund, 1931", "description": "The Athenian courts executed the Greek philosopher Socrates (469\\u2013399 B.C.) for the crime of impiety: his behavior toward the gods was judged to have been irreverent, and he had exerted a corrupting influence on his young male followers. Socrates declined to renounce his beliefs and died willingly, discoursing on the immortality of the soul before drinking from the cup of poisonous hemlock. In a prison of unrelieved severity, David depicted a frieze of carefully articulated figures in antique costume acting out in the language of gesture the last moments of the moral philosopher\\u2019s life. Because, shortly before the onset of the French revolution, the painting gave expression to the principle of resisting unjust authority, it is among David\\u2019s most important works. The canvas is also his most perfect statement of the Neoclassical style.", "classification": "Paintings", "accession_number": "31.45", "geographic_location": "Europe,France", "artist_maker_culture": "Jacques Louis David", "object_type_material": "Canvas,Oil paint,Paintings"}

column19: 9 of Horns, from The Cloisters Playing Cards
column23: {"date": "ca. 1475\\u201380", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/cl/web-large/DP354524.jpg", "title": "9 of Horns, from The Cloisters Playing Cards", "medium": "Paper (four layers of pasteboard) with pen and ink, opaque paint, glazes, and applied silver and gold", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/475530", "culture": "South Netherlandish", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1400\\u20131600", "geography": "Made in Burgundian territories", "dimensions": "5 3/16 \\xd7 2 3/4 in. (13.2 \\xd7 7 cm)", "credit_line": "The Cloisters Collection, 1983", "description": "The Cloisters set of fifty-two cards constitutes the only known complete deck of illuminated ordinary playing cards (as opposed to tarot cards) from the fifteenth century. There are four suits, each consisting of a king, queen, knave, and ten pip cards. The suit symbols, based on equipment associated with the hunt, are hunting horns, dog collars, hound tethers, and game nooses. The value of the pip cards is indicated by appropriate repetitions of the suit symbol. The figures, which appear to be based on Franco-Flemish models, were drawn in a bold, free, and engaging, if somewhat unrefined, hand. Their exaggerated and sometimes anachronistic costumes suggest a lampoon of extravagant Burgundian court fashions. Although some period card games are named, it is not known how they were played. Almost all card games did, however, involve some form of gambling. The condition of the set indicates that the cards were hardly used, if at all. It is possible that they were conceived as a collector\\u2019s curiosity rather than a deck for play.", "classification": "Miscellaneous-Paper", "accession_number": "1983.515.5", "geographic_location": "Europe,Netherlands", "object_type_material": "Glaze,Gold,Ink,Metal,Paper,Pen,Playing cards,Silver"}

One of its finest productions was this medieval romance written by the founder in the archaic style of Thomas Malory and beautifully illustrated by Edward Burne-Jones. In the full-page illustration, Friends in Need Meet in the Wild Wood, the young knight Ralph meets a maiden disguised in armor. Morris designed the elaborate ornamental border of grapevines, the embellished capital letter, and the typeface. Both imagery and text influenced writers J. R. R. Tolkien and C. S. column19: Amulet in the form of a head of an elephant
column23: {"date": "ca. 3500\\u20133300 B.C.", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/eg/web-large/DP109384.jpg", "title": "Amulet in the form of a head of an elephant", "medium": "SerpentiniteBone", "period": "Predynastic, Naqada II", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/547235", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "8000\\u20132000 B.C.", "geography": "From Egypt", "dimensions": "h. 3.5 x w. 3.6 x d. 2.1 cm (1 3/8 x 1 7/16 x 13/16 in.)", "credit_line": "Rogers Fund, 1959", "description": "Few amulets from the Predynastic Period are known. In the past, Egyptologists identified these amulets as representing a bull's head, but the round face and eyes, the horns that curve inward to the face, and a snout with a defined ridge make a strong argument for its identification as an elephant. During this period, elephants lived in oasis-like zones in the high desert created by greater rainfall than today. They were probably a rare sight to floodplain dwellers, but their size, tusks, and aggressive displays made them an awe-inspiring creature and an excellent subject for a potent amulet.", "accession_number": "59.101.1", "geographic_location": "Africa,Egypt", "object_type_material": "Amulets"}

column23: {"date": "ca. 1575\\u201387", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/es/web-large/DP326525.jpg", "title": "Dish", "artist": "Medici Porcelain Factory (Italian, Florence, ca. 1575\\u2013ca. 1587)", "medium": "Soft-paste porcelain", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/199761", "culture": "Italian, Florence", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1400\\u20131600", "dimensions": "Overall: 1 5/8 \\xd7 11 1/2 in. (4.1 \\xd7 29.2 cm)", "credit_line": "Gift of Mrs. Joseph V. McMullen, and Fletcher Fund, 1946", "description": "The porcelain made at the Medici workshops in Florence was the first to be produced in Europe. Francesco I de\\u2019Medici (1541\\u20131587) established a ceramic workshop in the 1560s with the intention of imitation Chinese blue-and-white porcelain. It took approximately ten years of experimentation before the workshop could manufacture the type of porcelain known as soft-paste. While so-called Medici porcelain lacks the ingredients that comprise hard-paste porcelain as made by the Chinese the Medici potters were able to craft a fine white ceramic body with cobalt decoration that represented an outstanding technical achievement for its time. Technically difficult and expensive to make, Medici porcelain was produced in very small quantities, and manufacture is believed to have ceased, or at least significantly diminished with the death of Francesco in 1587. Only fifty-nine pieces of Medici porcelain are known to have survive, of which one-tenth reside in the Museum's collection.", "classification": "Ceramics-Porcelain", "accession_number": "46.114", "geographic_location": "Europe,Florence,Italy,Tuscany", "artist_maker_culture": "Medici Porcelain Factory", "object_type_material": "Ceramics,Clay,Dishes,Glass,Glass paste,Porcelain,Soft paste porcelain"}

column23: {"date": "2nd half of 3rd century B.C.", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/gr/web-large/DP138733.jpg", "title": "Painted limestone funerary slab with a man controlling a rearing horse", "medium": "Limestone, paint", "period": "Hellenistic", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/247108", "culture": "Greek", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "1000 B.C.\\u2013A.D. 1", "dimensions": "Height: 15 1/2 \\xd7 10 1/2 \\xd7 2 7/8 in. (39.4 \\xd7 26.7 \\xd7 7.3 cm)", "credit_line": "Gift of Darius Ogden Mills, 1904", "description": "During the Ptolemaic period a distinctive type of subterranean tomb for multiple burials proliferated in the cemeteries around the city of Alexandria. Underground chambers cut into the living rock radiated from a central courtyard open to the sky. Most chambers contained a number of loculi, long narrow niches cut into the walls, which served as burial slots. Some loculi were sealed with painted limestone slabs in the form of small shrines. Here, a lively depiction of a man trying to bridle a horse, while a boy stands behind him, commemorates a man from Thessaly in Northern Greece, who must have been one of the many foreigners who congregated in the wealthy, cosmopolitan Ptolemaic capital.", "classification": "Miscellaneous-Paintings", "accession_number": "04.17.3", "geographic_location": "Europe,Greece", "object_type_material": "Limestone,Painting,Paintings,Stelae"}

(74.9 lb.)", "credit_line": "Gift of Samuel H. Kress Foundation, 1958", "description": "Works of art by the French artist Fran\\xe7ois Boucher (1703\\u20131770), who held the prestigious title of first painter to the king, served as a highly popular source of inspiration for artists working in a variety of media in the middle decades of the eighteenth century. Prints made after paintings by Boucher were widely circulated and provided artists with compositions that could be faithfully reproduced in smaller scale or adapted to three-dimensional porcelain sculpture. Works by Boucher served as the source not only for the painted scenes on vases and snuffboxes, but also for the porcelain figures which were listed as \"Enfants Boucher\" (Boucher Children) in the factory\\u2019s sales ledgers.", "classification": "Ceramics-Porcelain", "accession_number": "58.75.72a, b", "geographic_location": "Europe,France,S\\xe8vres", "artist_maker_culture": "Fran\\xe7ois Boucher,Charles Buteux,Charles Nicolas Dodin,S\\xe8vres Manufactory", "object_type_material": "Ceramics,Clay,Glass,Glass paste,Porcelain,Soft paste porcelain,Vases,Vessels"}

column23: {"date": "late 15th century", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/dp/web-large/DP167202.jpg", "title": "Album with Twelve Engravings of The Passion, a Woodcut of Christ as the Man of Sorrows, and a Metalcut of St. Jerome in Penitence", "artist": " Anonymous, German, Cologne, 15th century", "medium": "Engravings, two touched with gold;  woodcut, hand-colored; metalcut, hand-colored; manuscript in dark brown ink with red, and blue initials and flourishes; bound in blind-stamped leather.", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/363263", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1400\\u20131600", "dimensions": "Overall: 10 1/4 x 8 1/16 x 1/2 in. (26 x 20.4 x 1.3 cm)", "credit_line": "Purchase, Joseph Pulitzer Bequest and 2002 Benefit Fund; and The Chester Dale Collection, Bequest of Chester Dale, Gifts of Bessie Potter Vonnoh, Henry Walters and Anonymous, and other gifts, bequests, and funds, by exchange, 2003", "description": "This fascinating album provides vivid testimony to the way in which prints were used in the fifteenth century. Twelve outstanding early impressions of Israhel van Meckenem\\u2019s engravings of the Passion are interleaved with manuscript text of the Hundred Meditations on the Passion of Christ. The album also includes two rare devotional prints, both hand-colored, as well as liturgical calendars and several devotional texts in Dutch. The entirety was bound into a now well-worn fifteenth-century Netherlandish leather flap binding decorated with geometrical patterns and a stamp with animals and text.", "classification": "Albums", "accession_number": "2003.476", "geographic_location": "Europe,Germany", "artist_maker_culture": "Anonymous, German, Cologne, 15th century,Anonymous, Netherlandish, 15th century,Israhel van Meckenem", "object_type_material": "Albums,Books,Ink,Manuscripts,Prints,Relief prints,Stamping,Woodblock prints"}

column23: {"date": "1854", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ph/web-large/DP131340.jpg", "title": "J\\xe9rusalem, Couvent Arm\\xe9nien, Ornements, 1", "artist": "Auguste Salzmann (French, 1824\\u20131872)", "medium": "Salted paper print from paper negative", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/287013", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "printer": "Imprimerie photographique de Blanquart-\\xc9vrard, \\xe0 Lille (French, active 1851\\u201355)", "date_era": "A.D. 1800\\u20131900", "dimensions": "Image: 31 x 22.9 cm (12 3/16 x 9 in.)\\r\\nMount: 59.9 x 44.8 cm (23 9/16 x 17 5/8 in.)", "credit_line": "Gilman Collection, Gift of The Howard Gilman Foundation, 2005", "description": "Salzmann centers this composition on a covered window at what he identifies as an Armenian monastery. His vantage point emphasizes the textural variation among the intricate designs chiseled into the gridlike pattern of the stone wall. Shadows created by the sun\\u2019s high position outline the areas of carved relief and provide the contrast needed for a legible photograph. Although these examples of ornament hold significant cultural and religious meaning for the monastery\\u2019s inhabitants, Salzmann was interested only in their aesthetic qualities.", "classification": "Photographs", "accession_number": "2005.100.373.122", "geographic_location": "Europe,France", "artist_maker_culture": "Imprimerie photographique de Blanquart-\\xc9vrard, \\xe0 Lille,Auguste Salzmann", "object_type_material": "Photographs,Salted paper prints"}

column19: The Madonna of Humility, the Annunciation, the Nativity, and the Pietà
column23: {"date": "ca. 1465", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/rl/web-large/DT3056.jpg", "title": "The Madonna of Humility, the Annunciation, the Nativity, and the Piet\\xe0", "artist": "Bartolomeo Vivarini (Italian, active Venice 1450\\u201391)", "medium": "Tempera and gold on wood", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/459024", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1400\\u20131600", "dimensions": "Central panel, overall 23 x 18 in. (58.4 x 45.7 cm); left panel, overall 22 3/8 x 9 1/2 in. (56.8 x 24.1 cm); right panel, overall 22 1/4 x 9 3/8 in. (56.5 x 23.8 cm);", "credit_line": "Robert Lehman Collection, 1975", "description": "The Vivarini were a family of Venetian painters whose prolific workshop specialized in large multi-tiered altarpieces for churches throughout the Veneto region. This relatively small triptych was likely intended for private devotion. The kneeling nun, dressed as a member of the Dominican Order, probably represents the patron. Bartolomeo\\u2019s debt to the Paduan master Andrea Mantegna is especially evident in the rendering of the landscape and the figure of the Madonna in the Nativity scene. Although the frame is not original, it conveys the decorative ornamentation typical of the Vivarini.", "classification": "Paintings", "accession_number": "1975.1.82", "geographic_location": "Europe,Italy", "artist_maker_culture": "Bartolomeo Vivarini", "object_type_material": "Gold,Metal,Paintings,Tempera"}

column17: Clockmaker: Charles Dutertre (master clockmaker from 1758(?)), Porcelain by Sèvres Manufactory (French, 1740–present), French, Paris
column23: {"date": "ca. 1775", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/es/web-large/ES2678.jpg", "maker": "Clockmaker: Charles Dutertre (master clockmaker from 1758(?))", "title": "Clock", "medium": "Porcelain, enamel, gilt bronze, marble", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/199401", "culture": "French, Paris", "factory": "Porcelain by S\\xe8vres Manufactory (French, 1740\\u2013present)", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1600\\u20131800", "dimensions": "13 5/8 \\xd7 10 in. (34.6 \\xd7 25.4 cm)", "credit_line": "Gift of Ann Payne Blumenthal, 1943", "description": "About ten allegorical clocks of this model personifying love and friendship, probably created by the marchand mercier Dominique Daguerre (d. 1796), are known. Records of the S\\xe8vres porcelain manufactory indicate that twenty-three columns suitable for clock cases were supplied to Daguerre between 1772 and 1791. Holding two hearts in one hand, the female figure represents friendship; in her other hand, she originally held a portrait medallion, now missing. The putto on the other side of the column, personifying love, plays with a dog, the symbol of fidelity. A colored drawing for a similar clock, now in the Museum's collection, belongs to a group of drawings sent as a sort of sale catalogue to Albert, duke of Sachsen-Teschen, and his wife, Maria-Christina, a sister of Marie-Antoinette, joint governors of the Low Countries from 1780 to 1792.", "classification": "Horology", "accession_number": "43.163.24a, b", "geographic_location": "Europe,France,Paris", "artist_maker_culture": "Charles Dutertre,S\\xe8vres Manufactory", "object_type_material": "Bronze,Clay,Clocks,Copper alloy,Enamel,Gilt,Marble,Metal,Ormolu,Plate,Porcelain,Timepieces"}

{"date": "ca. 1800", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/mi/web-large/DP217184.jpg", "title": "Guitar", "medium": "Spruce, ebony, ivory, tortoiseshell, mother-of-pearl, brass", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/503932", "culture": "Italian", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "geography": "probably Naples, Italy", "dimensions": "Height: 36 in. (91.4 cm)Width: 10 5/8 in. (27 cm)Depth: 3 7/8 in. (9.8 cm)", "credit_line": "Rogers Fund, 1969", "description": "This highly decorated guitar is also an early example of a six-string, single-course guitar. The elaborate decoration features classical figures, musical instruments, and floral motifs made from ebony and fit into an ivory ground covering the back, sides, neck, and headstock of the guitar. A second guitar at the  Yale Collection of Musical Instruments features the same decoration, only in reverse, indicating that the decoration was made at the same time by cutting through thin layers of stacked ebony and ivory. A portrait in the center of the upper back is believed to be of Giovanni Paisiello based on his 1791 portrait. Paisiello was a composer of opera and many of his works were transcribed for use on other instruments and his pieces were a favorite of guitarists. The fingerboard is covered with tortoiseshell over read paint with an ivory satyr inlaid where the neck meets the body. A carved wooden rosette may be a replacement and is surrounded by an ivory hexagon with ebony inlaid instruments and flowers matching the back. The decorative style is evocative of so-called Baroque guitars of the seventeenth century. The six-string, single-course guitar became popular in Naples at the end of the eighteenth century and then spread throughout the rest of Europe replacing the earlier five and six double-course guitars.", "classification": "Chordophone-Lute-plucked-fretted", "accession_number": "69.29", "geographic_location": "Europe,Italy,Naples", "object_type_material": "Bone,Brass,Chordophones,Copper alloy,Ebony,Guitars,Ivory,Lutes,Metal,Musical instruments,Softwood,Spruce,Tortoise shell,Wood"}

(34.8 x 29.3 cm)", "credit_line": "Rogers Fund, 1971", "description": "This watercolor seems to have been intended as an artistic end in itself, since it is not a study for a known painting.  Panini did use the composition, however, in a series of pairs of paintings executed between 1756 and 1758, representing picture galleries crowded with many views of either ancient or modern Rome.  In the \"Roma Moderna\" of the first pair, which was commissioned by the Duke of Choiseul and is now in the Museum of Fine Arts, Boston, the Scalinata is seen from the same perspective as in this drawing.  The \"Roma Moderna\" of the second pair, which is also in the Metropolitan Museum (52.63.2), includes the Scalinata as well, on the floor to the left of the Duke, just as it is in the Boston painting.  In the third set, now in the Mus\\xe9e du Louvre, Paris, the Scalinata is high on the wall to the right.", "classification": "Drawings", "accession_number": "1971.63.1", "geographic_location": "Europe,Italy", "artist_maker_culture": "Giovanni Paolo Panini", "object_type_material": "Drawings,Graphite,Ink,Watercolors"}

column23: {"date": "early to mid 1480s", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/rl/web-large/DP324215.jpg", "title": "Study for the Equestrian Monument to Francesco Sforza", "artist": "Antonio Pollaiuolo (Italian, Florence ca. 1432\\u20131498 Rome)", "medium": "Pen and brown ink, light and dark brown wash; outlines of the horse and rider pricked for transfer.", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/459186", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1400\\u20131600", "dimensions": "11 1/16 x 10 in.  (28.1 x 25.4 cm)", "credit_line": "Robert Lehman Collection, 1975", "description": "This celebrated drawing was made by the Florentine painter, sculptor, engraver, and goldsmith Antonio Pollaiuolo. The sixteenth-century historian Giorgio Vasari, who owned the sheet and may have added the brown wash around the figures, seems to have described this drawing in his biography of Pollaiuolo (Lives of the Artists) of 1568. It represents a design for the bronze equestrian monument commissioned by Ludovico Sforza (1480-94, de facto ruler of Milan; 1494-99, Duke of Milan) in honor of his father, Francesco Sforza. This sheet (as well as its pendant, Staatliche Graphische Sammlung, Munich, inv. 1908.168) could have served as a presentation drawing for Ludovico, who may have arranged a competition between the artist and Leonardo da Vinci, who arrived at the Milanese court in the early 1480s. Leonardo, who won the commission, produced studies for the project from the early 1480s to the late 1490s, though the ill-fated monument was never completed.", "classification": "Drawings", "accession_number": "1975.1.410", "geographic_location": "Europe,Italy", "artist_maker_culture": "Antonio Pollaiuolo", "object_type_material": "Drawings,Ink,Pen,Pricking"}

This stela comes from a Rehuerdjersen's cenotaph at Abydos, and the style dates from the reign of Amenemhat II, some forty years after the treasurer's death. The owner is shown seated at the left, behind a table piled with stylized loaves of bread; at the right, holding a bird for offering, is his brother, Heqatifi, who commissioned the stela. The inscription consists largely of the names of other family members.", "accession_number": "12.182.1", "geographic_location": "Abydos,Africa,Egypt,Upper Egypt", "object_type_material": "Limestone,Stelae"}

column23: {"date": "ca. 1786\\u201391", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/dp/web-large/DP821142.jpg", "title": "A Rocky Stream, Italy", "artist": " Formerly attributed to John Downman (British, Ruabon, Wales 1750\\u20131824 Wrexham, Wales)", "medium": "Watercolor, pen and gray ink, over graphite", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/363695", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1600\\u20131800", "dimensions": "sheet: 14 3/4 x 19 1/2 in. (37.4 x 49.5 cm)", "credit_line": "Purchase, Jeffrey L. Berenson Gift, 2003", "description": "In addition to landscapes, Woodforde painted portraits and histories, contributing, for example, to Boydell's Shakespeare Gallery and to Macklin's Bible. He worked in Italy from 1786 to 1791, based in Rome and spending time with his most important patron Sir Richard Colt Hoare, who built Stourhead. It was probably on an excursion into the Campagna that he came upon the scene depicted here. At the center of the sheet, a large rock stands beside a rushing stream, flanked by foliage and surmounted by a small suspension bridge. An Italianate tower rises in the distance. Crisp pen lines combine with ink wash and subtly touches of watercolor to articulate a range of textures in a drawing that is at once descriptive and expressive.", "classification": "Drawings", "accession_number": "2003.524", "geographic_location": "Europe,United Kingdom,Wales", "artist_maker_culture": "John Downman,Samuel Woodforde", "object_type_material": "Drawings,Graphite,Ink,Watercolors"}

(99.7 x 73.7 cm)", "credit_line": "Purchase, 1871", "description": "Van Dyck was in Palermo, Sicily, when a plague broke out and the city was quarantined. On July 15, 1624, the remains of Saint Rosalie\\u2014the city\\u2019s patroness, who died about 1160\\u2014were opportunely discovered on Mount Pellegrino, which is visible here above the harbor of Palermo. Images of Saint Rosalie were in great demand; this one was painted by Van Dyck on top of a striking self-portrait that he had sketched on the canvas. The artist employed a design he had used earlier for paintings of the Assumption of the Virgin.", "classification": "Paintings", "accession_number": "71.41", "geographic_location": "Europe,Flanders", "artist_maker_culture": "Anthony van Dyck", "object_type_material": "Canvas,Oil paint,Paintings"}

{"date": "1856", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ph/web-large/DP267673.jpg", "title": "Oak Struck by Lightning, Badger, 1856.", "artist": "Alfred Capel Cure (British, 1826\\u20131896)", "medium": "Albumen silver print from paper negative", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/301892", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1800\\u20131900", "dimensions": "Image: 18 x 22.7 cm (7 1/16 x 8 15/16 in.)\\r\\nMount: 25.2 x 30.5 cm (9 15/16 x 12 in.)", "credit_line": "Purchase, The Buddy Taub Foundation Gift, Dennis A. Roach and Jill Roach, Directors, 2012", "description": "Cure joined the army at age eighteen, rising through the ranks to the level of major in 1855. Perhaps he saw the awkwardly arching limbs and shattered form of this young oak struck by lightning as an analogue for the agonies he had witnessed during the Crimean War, when so many colleagues and friends in his regiment were torn apart by shot and shell. This death portrait of a tree was made almost exactly a year after he was severely wounded and nearly lost his life leading his men successfully into battle during the siege of Sebastapol. Curiously, Cure accidentally killed himself while dynamiting the roots of a tree in his park, Badger Hall, some decades later.", "classification": "Photographs", "accession_number": "2012.112", "geographic_location": "Europe,United Kingdom", "artist_maker_culture": "Alfred Capel Cure", "object_type_material": "Albumen silver prints,Photographs"}

{"date": "1900s, printed 1909", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ph/web-large/DP263573.jpg", "title": "Adam and Eve", "artist": "Frank Eugene (American, New York 1865\\u20131936 Munich)", "medium": "Photogravure", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/260240", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1900\\u2013present", "dimensions": "17.8 x 12.8 cm. (7  x 5  1/16  in.)", "credit_line": "Rogers Fund, 1972", "description": "Born in New York to immigrant parents, Eugene was one of many young German-Americans to travel to Munich to study at the Royal Bavarian Academy of Arts. Alfred Stieglitz and the influential art critic Sadakichi Hartmann promoted Eugene\\u2019s Pictorialist photographs in exhibitions and publications such as Camera Work, where this photograph appeared in 1910. Eugene\\u2019s interest in a variety of artistic media is seen in the bold manipulation of his negatives. He used paintbrushes, etching needles, and pencils to rework his compositions, thus proclaiming their status as art. This photogravure\\u2014a print created from a photomechanically etched copper plate\\u2014depicts a classic subject from the annals of art history, the deep chiaroscuro and scratched surface suggesting Adam and Eve after the fall.", "classification": "Photographs", "accession_number": "1972.633.33", "geographic_location": "North and Central America,United States", "artist_maker_culture": "Frank Eugene", "object_type_material": "Photographs,Photogravures,Photomechanical reproductions"}
