column19: Dish with a scene of tea cultivation (one of a pair)
column23: {"date": "ca. 1740\\u201345", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/es/web-large/196007.jpg", "title": "Dish with a scene of tea cultivation (one of a pair)", "medium": "Hard-paste porcelain painted with cobalt blue under transparent glaze (Jingdezhen ware)", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/205312", "culture": "Chinese, for European (probably Dutch) market", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1600\\u20131800", "dimensions": "Overall: 1 5/16 \\xd7 13 3/4 in. (3.3 \\xd7 34.9 cm)", "credit_line": "Helena Woolworth McCann Collection, Purchase, Winfield Foundation Gift, 1971", "description": "These dishes belonged to a table service decorated with scenes of the cultivation of tea. The upper dish illustrates the production of metal containers for transporting tea. The lower one depicts rattan being applied to the outside of a container, while on the right a man is packing tea by stomping it down. These cylindrical containers were used to transport the tea to Canton, where it was repacked in metal-lined wooden chests for shipment to Europe and elsewhere. Chinese potters' borrowing of French pottery motifs for the border design speaks to the stylistic cross-currents enabled by the extensive trade in the eighteenth century.", "classification": "Ceramics-Porcelain-Export", "accession_number": "1971.32.2", "geographic_location": "Asia,China", "object_type_material": "Ceramics,Clay,Cobalt,Dishes,Glass,Glass paste,Glaze,Metal,Painting,Porcelain"}

column23: {"date": "1589", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/dp/web-large/DP158476.jpg", "title": "Still Life with Flowers, a Snail and Insects", "artist": "Joris Hoefnagel (Netherlandish, Antwerp 1542\\u20131601 Vienna)", "medium": "Watercolor, gouache, and shell gold on vellum", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/382608", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1400\\u20131600", "dimensions": "Sheet: 4 5/8 x 3 11/16 in. (11.7 x 9.3 cm)", "credit_line": "Purchase, Charles and Jessie Price, Jean A. Bonna, and Annette de la Renta Gifts, and The Elisha Whittelsey Collection, The Elisha Whittelsey Fund, 2008", "description": "Joris Hoefnagel is one of a few artists in the sixteenth century, celebrated for their incredibly accurate and beautiful studies after nature. The symmetric composition of this bouquet might give it a gloss of artifice from a modern viewpoint, but conforms to the predominant taste that lasted well into the seventeenth century. The difference in scale of some of Hoefnagel\\u2019s flowers indicates that he used individual flower studies to form his bouquet; a fact that is supported by his reuse of separate motifs in other works. This particular bouquet of flowers is a very intimate work, not just because of its size, but also because of its intended purpose. The Latin inscription on the pedestal reveals that Hoefnagel made this drawing for his mother \\u2018as a monument of love\\u2019.", "classification": "Drawings", "accession_number": "2008.110", "geographic_location": "Europe,Netherlands", "artist_maker_culture": "Joris Hoefnagel", "object_type_material": "Drawings,Gouache,Parchment,Vellum,Watercolors"}

{"date": "17th\\u201318th century", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/es/web-large/7996.jpg", "title": "Wall tile", "medium": "Tin-glazed and luster-painted earthenware", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/187790", "culture": "Spanish, Seville", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1600\\u20131800", "dimensions": "Width: 12 3/4 in. (32.4 cm)", "credit_line": "Gift of Henry G. Marquand, 1894", "description": "Tin-glazed earthenware, of which lusterware is one type, was developed in the Middle East in the ninth and tenth centuries to imitate the porcelains produced in China. The opaque white glaze concealed the clay body, which could range from pale buff to brick red, allowing for brilliant effects created by painting the white surface with metal oxides that fired to a range of colors. This technique, as well as the use of metallic luster\\u2014an iridescent, coppery painted glaze\\u2014spread throughout the Muslim world, arriving among the potters of Valencia in the thirteenth century. The so-called Hispano-Moresque lusterware, with its fusion of Islamic and Gothic styles and motifs, often in shaped imitating those of metal vessels, was treasured by the elite in Spain during the fifteenth century and exported to the courts of Europe. The Valencian industry declined in the late sixteenth century, as colorful Italian Renaissance maiolica gained in popularity among the fashionable and as Spanish centers were founded to produce versions of its pictorial forms. Adding to this decline was the expulsion from Valencia in 1609 of all the remaining Moriscos (Muslims converted to Christianity), though Christian potters reestablished the industry shortly thereafter.", "classification": "Ceramics-Pottery", "accession_number": "94.4.179", "geographic_location": "Andalusia,Europe,Seville,Spain", "object_type_material": "Ceramics,Earthenware,Glazing,Luster,Painting,Pottery,Tile,Wall tile"}

column23: {"date": "ca. 1415\\u201317", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/md/web-large/DP144070.jpg", "title": "Virgin and Child", "artist": "Attributed to Claus de Werve (Netherlandish, active in France, ca. 1380\\u20131439, active Burgundy, 1396\\u2013ca. 1439)", "medium": "Limestone with paint and gilding", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/467594", "culture": "French", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1400\\u20131600", "geography": "Made in Poligny, Burgundy", "dimensions": "Overall: 53 3/8 x 41 1/8 x 27 in. (135.5 x 104.5 x 68.6 cm)", "credit_line": "Rogers Fund, 1933", "description": "This monumental yet intimate image of the Virgin and Child was probably a gift of John the Fearless, Duke of Burgundy (d. 1419), or his wife, Margaret of Bavaria (d. 1424), to the convent they founded dedicated to the Franciscan order of Poor Clares at Poligny. As court sculptor to the Burgundian dukes in Dijon, the influential artist Claus de Werve, to whom this sculpture is attributed, created many works for his patrons, and this sculpture is one of his masterpieces. The curly-headed child Jesus looks up at his mother as she balances him and a large book on her lap. This tender moment between mother and son is, at the same time, a presentation of a sophisticated theological theme. The clue to understanding it is the Latin inscription on the bench. Taken from the Book of Ecclesiasticus, dedicated to and extolling wisdom, it reads, \"From the beginning, and before the world, was I created\" (24:14). Although by the thirteenth century the Church applied this text, which refers to Wisdom as a feminine entity, to discuss Mary, it was Christ as God incarnate who was seen as the personification of divine Wisdom on earth and Mary the vessel, or throne, that bore him.", "classification": "Sculpture-Stone", "accession_number": "33.23", "geographic_location": "Burgundy,Europe,France", "artist_maker_culture": "Claus de Werve", "object_type_material": "Gilt,Limestone,Sculpture,Statues,Stone"}

{"date": "1744\\u201345", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/es/web-large/ES7223.jpg", "title": "Snuffbox", "medium": "Gold, mother-of-pearl", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/206413", "culture": "French, Paris", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1600\\u20131800", "dimensions": "Overall: 1 3/8 \\xd7 2 15/16 \\xd7 2 1/4 in. (3.5 \\xd7 7.5 \\xd7 5.7 cm)", "credit_line": "Gift of Mr. and Mrs. Charles Wrightsman, 1976", "description": "In eighteenth-century Europe, Paris led the production of high-quality luxury goods. Parisian goldsmiths made a wide range of small, personal articles such as snuffboxes; \\xe9tuis to hold sealing wax, tweezers, or utensils for sewing; souvenirs, which contained thin ivory tablets for note taking; and shuttles for knotting lace. Gold snuffboxes and boxes decorated with portrait miniatures were prized and frequently given as royal gifts, often to ambassadors or members of the court in lieu of cash payments for their services. Coveted and admired, these boxes were produced from a variety of materials. The best were skillfully made of gold and embellished with diamonds, enameled decoration, lacquer, and other luxurious materials. By the middle of the century, the taking of snuff had become an entrenched social ritual, and the snuffbox, too, had become an important social prop. Snuffboxes were considered highly fashionable accessories, with some merchants advertising new boxes with each change of season. The popularity of snuffboxes extended to all levels of society, and for those who could not afford gold, boxes were produced in less expensive materials such as silver, tortoiseshell, porcelain, or domestically produced lacquer.", "classification": "Metalwork-Gold and Platinum", "accession_number": "1976.155.12", "geographic_location": "Europe,France,Paris", "object_type_material": "Gold,Metal,Metalwork,Mother of pearl,Platinum,Snuff containers,Snuffboxes"}

column19: Vessel in the form of a boar
column23: {"date": "ca. 3100\\u20132900 B.C.", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/an/web-large/DT4907.jpg", "title": "Vessel in the form of a boar", "medium": "Ceramic, paint", "period": "Proto-Elamite", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/326617", "culture": "Proto-Elamite", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "8000\\u20132000 B.C.", "geography": "Southwestern Iran", "dimensions": "5.71 in. (14.5 cm)", "credit_line": "Purchase, Rogers Fund and Anonymous Gift, 1979", "description": "This ceramic vessel takes the form of a standing wild boar. The body is hollow, serving as a container, with a small round rim atop the center of the back and a hole pierced through the snout. The vessel could have been filled through the larger hole in the back while the smaller hole in the snout was held closed with a thumb, allowing the liquid to flow out once the snout was uncovered. Made of fine clay with a smoothed surface, the vessel is decorated in dark brown paint on buff-colored ceramic. The sharply angled hatching covering the vessel evokes the boar\\u2019s bristly hide, especially along the spine, where it is arranged in a vertical row. The eyes are indicated by circles with a central dot, just below the small, alertly raised ears. The split hooves and fetlocks are modeled in clay. The boar\\u2019s hunched posture lends the vessel a sense of potentially explosive movement, and reminds the viewer that wild boars are fierce animals that pose dangers to crops in the field, and to the hunters pursuing them. Similar zoomorphic, or animal-shaped, vessels are especially characteristic of the Proto-Elamite period (3100-2900 B.C.) in southwestern Iran.", "classification": "Ceramics-Vessels", "accession_number": "1979.71", "geographic_location": "Asia,Iran", "artist_maker_culture": "Elamite,Proto-Elamite", "object_type_material": "Ceramics,Vessels"}

column19: Snuffbox with portrait of Louis XVI (1754–1793), King of France
column23: {"date": "1779\\u201380", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/es/web-large/DP-594-005.jpg", "maker": "Joseph \\xc9tienne Blerzy (French, active 1750\\u20131806)", "title": "Snuffbox with portrait of Louis XVI (1754\\u20131793), King of France", "artist": "Miniature by Louis Marie Sicardi (French, Avignon 1743\\u20131825 Paris)", "medium": "Gold, enamel, diamonds; ivory, glass", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/196539", "culture": "French, Paris", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1600\\u20131800", "dimensions": "1 3/8 x 3 1/4 x 2 1/2 in. (3.5 x 8.3 x 6.4cm); Miniature: oval, 1 1/4 x 1 in. (32 x 25 mm)", "credit_line": "Bequest of Edward C. Post, 1930", "description": "In eighteenth-century Europe, Paris led the production of high-quality luxury goods. Parisian goldsmiths made a wide range of small, personal articles such as snuffboxes; \\xe9tuis to hold sealing wax, tweezers, or utensils for sewing; souvenirs, which contained thin ivory tablets for note taking; and shuttles for knotting lace. Gold snuffboxes and boxes decorated with portrait miniatures were prized and frequently given as royal gifts, often to ambassadors or members of the court in lieu of cash payments for their services. Coveted and admired, these boxes were produced from a variety of materials. The best were skillfully made of gold and embellished with diamonds, enameled decoration, lacquer, and other luxurious materials. By the middle of the century, the taking of snuff had become an entrenched social ritual, and the snuffbox, too, had become an important social prop. Snuffboxes were considered highly fashionable accessories, with some merchants advertising new boxes with each change of season. The popularity of snuffboxes extended to all levels of society, and for those who could not afford gold, boxes were produced in less expensive materials such as silver, tortoiseshell, porcelain, or domestically produced lacquer.", "classifications": "Metalwork-Gold and Platinum, Miniatures", "accession_number": "30.58.3", "geographic_location": "Europe,France,Paris", "artist_maker_culture": "Joseph \\xc9tienne Blerzy,Louis Marie Sicardi", "object_type_material": "Bone,Diamond,Enamel,Glass,Gold,Ivory,Metal,Metalwork,Miniatures,Paintings,Platinum,Snuff containers,Snuffboxes"}

column23: {"date": "March 1, 1866", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/dp/web-large/DP319835.jpg", "title": "Ophelia (Shakespeare, Hamlet, Act 4, Scene 7)", "artist": "After Sir John Everett Millais (British, Southampton 1829\\u20131896 London)", "medium": "Mezzotint, etching and stipple on chine coll\\xe9; proof", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/368061", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "subject": "William Shakespeare (British, Stratford-upon-Avon 1564\\u20131616 Stratford-upon-Avon)", "date_era": "A.D. 1800\\u20131900", "engraver": "James Stephenson (British, Manchester 1808\\u20131886 London)", "publisher": "Henry Graves & Company (London)", "dimensions": "Image: 20 11/16 in. \\xd7 34 in. (52.5 \\xd7 86.3 cm)\\r\\nPlate: 25 7/16 \\xd7 37 1/16 in. (64.6 \\xd7 94.2 cm)\\r\\nSheet: 27 3/8 x 39 3/16 in. (69.5 x 99.5 cm)\\r\\nChine coll\\xe9: 24 5/16 \\xd7 35 13/16 in. (61.7 \\xd7 90.9 cm)", "credit_line": "The Elisha Whittelsey Collection, The Elisha Whittelsey Fund, 1949", "description": "Here, Hamlet\\u2019s rejected lover, her mind unhinged, has fallen into a brook while picking wildflowers. Inspired by an evocative description of Ophelia\\u2019s death in Shakespeare\\u2019s Hamlet (act 4, scene 7), Millais painted the subject for a London Royal Academy exhibition in 1852; this masterful print reproduces that composition. As a member of the Pre-Raphaelite Brotherhood, Millais challenged artistic convention and spent months outdoors painting the lush setting, and then posed a model in a bathtub in his studio to complete the composition. The painting\\u2019s hyperrealistic detail and collapsed space initially unsettled viewers, but this later print encouraged admiration for the groundbreaking conception. Stephenson combined mezzotint, etching, and stipple to evoke the rich silverwork adorning Ophelia\\u2019s gown and describe the range of plants and flowers embellishing her watery grave.", "classification": "Prints", "accession_number": "49.40.282", "geographic_location": "Europe,United Kingdom", "artist_maker_culture": "Henry Graves & Company,Sir John Everett Millais,William Shakespeare,James Stephenson", "object_type_material": "Chine coll\\xe9,Engravings,Etching,Intaglio prints,Mezzotints,Prints,Proofs,Stippling"}

column19: Relief with two royal male figures
column23: {"date": "ca. 1353\\u20131336 B.C.", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/eg/web-large/DP137142.jpg", "reign": "reign of Akhenaten", "title": "Relief with two royal male figures", "medium": "Limestone, paint", "period": "New Kingdom, Amarna Period", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/547769", "dynasty": "Dynasty 18", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "2000\\u20131000 B.C.", "geography": "From Egypt, Middle Egypt, Amarna (Akhetaten)", "dimensions": "H. 23.5 \\xd7 W. 37 cm (9 1/4 \\xd7 14 9/16 in.)", "credit_line": "Purchase, The Abner Rosen Foundation Inc. Gift and Ludlow Bull Fund, 2006", "description": "This relief depicts the torsos of two figures, a larger one on the left and a smaller one on the right. The figure on the right is clearly a male, and the figure on the left must also be a male because the angle of the garment pleats identify it as the male sash-kilt. The clothing along with the intimacy of the grouping thus indicate two male members of the Amarna royal family are depicted. Given the size differential of the two figures, it is perhaps more likely that Smenkhare and Tutankhaten as brothers (?) are depicted, rather than Akhenaten and Smenkhkare as coregents.", "accession_number": "2006.102", "geographic_location": "Africa,Amarna,Egypt,Upper Egypt", "object_type_material": "Figures,Limestone,Reliefs,Sculpture"}

{"date": "1867", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ph/web-large/DT203401.jpg", "title": "Multnomah Falls Cascade, Columbia River", "artist": "Carleton E. Watkins (American, 1829\\u20131916)", "medium": "Albumen silver print from glass negative", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/283221", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1800\\u20131900", "dimensions": "Image: 52.4 x 40 cm (20 5/8 x 15 3/4 in.)\\r\\nMount: 64.7 x 49.5 cm (25 1/2 x 19 1/2 in.)", "credit_line": "Gilman Collection, Purchase, The Horace W. Goldsmith Foundation Gift, through Joyce and Robert Menschel, 2005", "description": "In 1867, Watkins made a four-month trip to Oregon and the Columbia River. Josiah Whitney accompanied him for the first month and helped finance the excursion. Watkins had photographed the Nevada, Vernal, and Yosemite Falls before he went to Oregon; on those occasions, he either described the waterfalls as elements within broader landscapes (on the mammoth plates) or made close-up shots of the water roaring over the rocks (for stereo viewing). In this marvelously minimal photograph, he seems to have applied the simplicity of effect he usually reserved for stereographs to the monumental mammoth plate; boldly reducing the cascade to its essentials, white water cleaves dark rock in a single stroke, like liquid lightning.", "classification": "Photographs", "accession_number": "2005.100.108", "geographic_location": "North and Central America,United States", "artist_maker_culture": "Carleton E. column19: Top of standard with male figure and flanking ibexes attacked by dogs
column23: {"date": "ca. 1500\\u20131100 B.C.", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/an/web-large/DP370180.jpg", "title": "Top of standard with male figure and flanking ibexes attacked by dogs", "medium": "Bronze", "period": "Middle Elamite", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/324579", "culture": "Elamite", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "2000\\u20131000 B.C.", "geography": "Southwestern Iran", "dimensions": "11 3/4 x 4 3/4in. (29.8 x 12.1cm)", "credit_line": "Harris Brisbane Dick Fund, 1957", "description": "One of a pair, this cast bronze element was attached to a pole by the curved tang at the bottom. A hollow ring with ropelike ridges and incised rosettes in between is surmounted by a solid-cast striding male figure wearing a knee-length belted garment and boots with upturned toes. A snake supports his front foot. He holds an object, possibly an animal, at his chest while raising the other hand in a gesture of supplication. He has both a mustache and beard, and his hair projects slightly at the front. He is flanked by two solid recumbent horned animals whose haunches are attacked by crouching dogs. The style of the male figure and the snake point to Elam as the place of manufacture. The meaning of such an unusual composition is not known, but similar male figures are found among Elamite votive images.", "classification": "Metalwork-Sculpture", "accession_number": "57.13.1", "geographic_location": "Asia,Iran", "artist_maker_culture": "Elamite", "object_type_material": "Bronze,Copper alloy,Figures,Metal,Metalwork,Sculpture"}

{"date": "ca. 1880", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/mi/web-large/DP152107a.jpg", "title": "Rattle", "medium": "Wood, string, pigment", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/502542", "culture": "Native American (Haida or Tsimshian)", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1800\\u20131900", "geography": "British Columbia, Canada", "dimensions": "Height: 11 1/2 in. (29.2 cm)\\r\\nDiameter: 6 in. (15.2 cm)", "credit_line": "The Crosby Brown Collection of Musical Instruments, 1889", "description": "Rattles like this were most likely used during dance rituals of the Haida or Tsimshian. Spherical in shape with two diametrically opposed faces, this rattle represents typical carving of Northwest Coast people, exhibiting form-line carving in low relief. The cutaway\\u2014darkened\\u2014sections represent an equally significant aspect of the composition. Low-relief carving in this style makes a play on the relationship between negative and positive space. One side of the rattle depicts a face in quintessential form-line ornament, with ovoid and U-shaped realizations of the space between the form-lines. The opposite side of the rattle depicts a hook-nosed bird figure, possibly a hawk or raven, the nose protruding from the low relief of the face. There is evidence of red and black pigment as embellishment on both sides of rattle. This wooden rattle is constructed in two pieces carved to form a hollow chamber. Small holes carved near edges of both pieces are threaded with vegetal lacing and pinned with iron nails to secure the two halves together, along with the wrapping at the base of handle.", "classification": "Idiophone-Shaken-rattle", "accession_number": "89.4.1963", "geographic_location": "Canada,North and Central America", "artist_maker_culture": "Haida", "object_type_material": "Cord,Idiophones,Musical instruments,Rattles,Wood"}

The likenesses of Tad and the president derive from a photograph Anthony Berger took in Mathew Brady\\u2019s Washington gallery on February 9, 1864, a few days before the president\\u2019s fifty-fifth birthday. The bible that Lincoln reads introduces a spiritual tone\\u2014in the photograph the president peruses an album\\u2014heightened by the small landscape on the back wall that depicts a ship sailing toward the setting sun, watched by a lone figure on shore.", "classification": "Prints", "accession_number": "63.550.511", "geographic_location": "North and Central America,United States", "artist_maker_culture": "Currier & Ives,Abraham Lincoln,Mary Todd Lincoln,Robert Todd Lincoln,Thomas \"Tad\" Lincoln,G. {"date": "1513", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/dp/web-large/DP102226.jpg", "title": "Knight, Death, and the Devil", "artist": "Albrecht D\\xfcrer (German, Nuremberg 1471\\u20131528 Nuremberg)", "medium": "Engraving", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/336223", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1400\\u20131600", "dimensions": "Sheet: 9 13/16 x 7 11/16 in. (25 x 19.6 cm)\\r\\nPlate: 9 9/16 x 7 3/8 in. (24.3 x 18.8 cm)", "credit_line": "Harris Brisbane Dick Fund, 1943", "description": "D\\xfcrer's Knight, Death, and the Devil is one of three large prints of 1513\\u201314 known as his Meisterstiche (master engravings). The other two are Melancholia I and Saint Jerome in His Study. Though not a trilogy in the strict sense, the prints are closely interrelated and complementary, corresponding to the three kinds of virtue in medieval scholasticism\\u2014theological, intellectual, and moral. Called simply the Reuter (Rider) by D\\xfcrer, Knight, Death, and the Devil embodies the state of moral virtue. The artist may have based his depiction of the \"Christian Knight\" on an address from Erasmus's Instructions for the Christian Soldier (Enchiridion militis Christiani), published in 1504: \"In order that you may not be deterred from the path of virtue because it seems rough and dreary ... and because you must constantly fight three unfair enemies\\u2014the flesh, the devil, and the world\\u2014this third rule shall be proposed to you: all of those spooks and phantoms which come upon you as if you were in the very gorges of Hades must be deemed for naught after the example of Virgil's Aeneas ... Look not behind thee.\" Riding steadfastly through a dark Nordic gorge, D\\xfcrer's knight rides past Death on a Pale Horse, who holds out an hourglass as a reminder of life's brevity, and is followed closely behind by a pig-snouted Devil. As the embodiment of moral virtue, the rider\\u2014modeled on the tradition of heroic equestrian portraits with which D\\xfcrer was familiar from Italy\\u2014is undistracted and true to his mission. A haunting expression of the vita activa, or active life, the print is a testament to the way in which D\\xfcrer's thought and technique coalesced brilliantly in the \"master engravings.\"", "classification": "Prints", "accession_number": "43.106.2", "geographic_location": "Europe,Germany", "artist_maker_culture": "Albrecht D\\xfcrer", "object_type_material": "Engraving,Prints"}

column17: Andrea Zambelli "L Honnesta" (Italian, active 1732–1772), Italian, Venice
column23: {"date": "ca. 1740\\u201350", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/es/web-large/DP334410.jpg", "title": "Torah crown (keter)", "medium": "Silver, parcel gilt", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/239512", "culture": "Italian, Venice", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1600\\u20131800", "dimensions": "Overall (confirmed, irregular diameter): 10 13/16 \\xd7 12 3/8 \\xd7 12 3/8 in. (27.5 \\xd7 31.4 \\xd7 31.4 cm)", "credit_line": "Director's Fund, 2013", "description": "Exceptional for its size and precious material, this Torah crown is a rare survival of 18th-century Italian silver and a testimony to the artistic virtuosity of goldsmithing in Venice. In synagogues the scroll of the Torah, the first five books of the Hebrew Bible, is often decorated with a set of vestments and silver ornaments including a crown or finials, and a shield. The crown augments the Torah\\u2019s status as an object associated with royalty and speaks to the centrality of the Torah in Jewish life. The motifs depicted include ritual references such as priestly garments, a miniature temple, a menorah, and the Tablets of the Law, the latter engraved in Hebrew with the Ten Commandments. Such rich embellishment is indicative of the wealth and influential status of the Jewish congregation in the Venetian city state. The maker, Andrea Zambelli, is known to have made a wide range of ritual Judaica as well as religious silver for the local churches. A later inscription in Hebrew documents that this \"crown of glory, and diadem of beauty\" [Isaiah 28:5], was given by the philanthropist and president of the Jewish community in Padua, Gabriel Trieste, to his congregation in the mid-19th century.", "silversmith": "Andrea Zambelli \"L'Honnesta\" (Italian, active 1732\\u20131772)", "classification": "Metalwork-Silver", "accession_number": "2013.443", "geographic_location": "Europe,Italy,Venice", "artist_maker_culture": "Andrea Zambelli \"L'Honnesta\"", "object_type_material": "Crowns,Gilt,Metal,Metalwork,Silver"}

column23: {"date": "ca. 1500\\u20131504", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ep/web-large/DT1459.jpg", "title": "The Marriage Feast at Cana", "artist": "Juan de Flandes (Netherlandish, active by 1496\\u2013died 1519 Palencia)", "medium": "Oil on wood", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/436801", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1400\\u20131600", "dimensions": "8 1/4 x 6 1/4 in. (21 x 15.9 cm)", "credit_line": "The Jack and Belle Linsky Collection, 1982", "description": "This was one of forty-seven panels representing the lives of Christ and the Virgin that were made for Isabella of Castile. The picture\\u2019s subject is the marriage feast at Cana, when Christ performed his first miracle turning water into wine. The convex mirror, seen behind the married couple, is a common motif in Netherlandish painting. The preparatory underdrawing reveals a number of anecdotal details that were never painted. Their elimination could be indicative of the painter\\u2019s moving from a Flemish to a more Spanish mode, and may reflect the more austere style of presentation favored by Isabella and her religious advisors.", "classification": "Paintings", "accession_number": "1982.60.20", "geographic_location": "Europe,Netherlands", "artist_maker_culture": "Juan de Flandes", "object_type_material": "Oil paint,Paintings"}

column17: Pierre Jean David d Angers (French, Angers 1788–1856 Paris), French, Paris
column23: {"date": "1828", "image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/es/web-large/31572.jpg", "title": "Ferdinand Victor Eug\\xe8ne Delacroix (1799\\u20131863)", "artist": "Pierre Jean David d'Angers (French, Angers 1788\\u20131856 Paris)", "medium": "Bronze, brown patina", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/188442", "culture": "French, Paris", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1800\\u20131900", "dimensions": "Diameter: 4 1/4 in. (10.8 cm)", "credit_line": "Gift of Samuel P. Avery, 1898", "description": "Pierre-Jean David d\\u2019Angers was the most prolific and one of the most important French sculptors of the first half of the nineteenth century. Throughout his almost fifty-year career (1819\\u20131856) David remained true to his conviction that sculptural monuments dedicated to the achievements of great men and women most permanently and vividly express the greatness of a people. He continuously sought commissions for monuments portraying historical and contemporary figures whom he admired in order to commit their contributions to posterity. His most famous public commission, the figurative pediment of the Pantheon in Paris (1830\\u20131837), which commemorates great men and was dedicated by a grateful nation, exemplifies these life-long principles. \\n\\nDavid d\\u2019Angers extended his definition of public monuments to include portrait medallions. In the 1820s he dedicated himself to a personal campaign of creating contemporary and retrospective medallic portraits of illustrious sitters. By the end of his life David had executed almost five-hundred portrait medallions, frequently travelling great distances to model his sitters from life. The medallions most often were not commissioned. David himself chose whom he deemed worthy of inclusion into his medallic pantheon. David also did not profit from the portraits. He generally delivered his wax models to professional founders for casting and dissemination through sale.", "classification": "Medals and Plaquettes", "accession_number": "98.7.36", "geographic_location": "Europe,France,Paris", "artist_maker_culture": "Pierre Jean David d'Angers", "object_type_material": "Bronze,Copper alloy,Medallions,Medals,Metal,Patina,Plaquettes,Sculpture"}

The manuscript to which this painting belongs was likely copied in Herat, but it was illustrated for an Uzbek patron several years later, probably in Bukhara in the 1530s.  The Bukharan school of painting, which was influenced by the Herat style, is characterized by a bright palette and the use of a black ground to set off fine arabesque designs. Kress Foundation, 1958", "description": "Works of art by the French artist Fran\\xe7ois Boucher (1703\\u20131770), who held the prestigious title of first painter to the king, served as a highly popular source of inspiration for artists working in a variety of media in the middle decades of the eighteenth century. Prints made after paintings by Boucher were widely circulated and provided artists with compositions that could be faithfully reproduced in smaller scale or adapted to three-dimensional porcelain sculpture. Works by Boucher served as the source not only for the painted scenes on vases and snuffboxes, but also for the porcelain figures which were listed as \"Enfants Boucher\" (Boucher Children) in the factory\\u2019s sales ledgers.", "manufactory": "S\\xe8vres Manufactory (French, 1740\\u2013present)", "classification": "Ceramics-Porcelain", "accession_number": "58.75.73a, b", "geographic_location": "Europe,France,S\\xe8vres", "artist_maker_culture": "Fran\\xe7ois Boucher,Charles Buteux,Charles Nicolas Dodin,S\\xe8vres Manufactory", "object_type_material": "Ceramics,Clay,Glass,Glass paste,Porcelain,Soft paste porcelain,Vases,Vessels"}

column23: {"date": "modeled 1897, cast 1972", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/es/web-large/DP-13618-017.jpg", "title": "Final Study for the Monument to Balzac", "artist": "Auguste Rodin (French, Paris 1840\\u20131917 Meudon)", "medium": "Bronze", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/207498", "culture": "French", "founder": "Cast by Georges Rudier (French)", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "dimensions": "Overall (wt. confirmed): 41 3/4 \\xd7 17 1/2 \\xd7 16 1/2 in., 114 lb. (106 \\xd7 44.5 \\xd7 41.9 cm, 51.7 kg)", "credit_line": "Gift of Iris and B. Gerald Cantor Foundation, 1984", "description": "In 1891 Rodin was commissioned to construct a posthumous monument to the illustrious literary figure Honor\\xe9 de Balzac. It took the sculptor seven years to arrive at the final study from which this bronze was cast. Gaze fixed toward the horizon, a disheveled Balzac leans back, his body transformed by a shapeless oversize cloak into a dense and formidable monolith. \\tToday Balzac\\u2019s shrouded figure is understood to be symbolic of the author\\u2019s imposing genius. Contemporary viewers, however, were baffled by its inarticulate form. The work provoked harsh criticism upon its debut in 1898, but Rodin defended it, explaining that \"a man celebrated for his heart and mind should not be [represented by] his body.\"", "classification": "Sculpture-Bronze", "accession_number": "1984.364.15", "geographic_location": "Europe,France", "artist_maker_culture": "Auguste Rodin,Georges Rudier", "object_type_material": "Bronze,Copper alloy,Metal,Sculpture,Statues"}

{"date": "5th\\u20136th century", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ao/web-large/DP102149.jpg", "title": "Portrait Head Bottle", "medium": "Ceramic", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/308527", "culture": "Moche", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "geography": "Peru", "dimensions": "Overall: 12 3/4 in. (32.39 cm)", "credit_line": "Gift of Mr. and Mrs. Nathan Cummings, 1964", "description": "The Moche peoples were prolific potters. They produced thousands of ceramic vessels\\u2014primarily stirrup-spout bottles\\u2014for use in rituals and mortuary events. The so-called portrait head vessels, such as this, which may depict important individuals in Moche society perhaps at different stages of their lives, have distinctive facial features with varied expressions. Age differences appear as well, for instance, wrinkles for age were modeled onto the face before firing. This portrait head wears a head cloth over his hair; a band decorated with four serpents, two on each side, is worked around the crown of the head. The profile serpents have open mouths, rows of bared teeth, and bifurcated tongues. They face each other in the center of the forehead. The face is painted\\u2014along the nose bridge, a triangle from nose to mouth, and a larger rectangle on each cheek. This pattern is seen on prominent people and even on major gods in Moche art. (64.8 x 16.5 x 10.2 cm)", "credit_line": "The Cloisters Collection, 1947", "description": "This container for the precious remains of a saint adopts the form of the relics it likely once held\\u2014fragments of a saint\\u2019s arm. When the reliquary was set on an altar, the sacred bones could be perceived in the two windows, once covered with crystal, which are cut into the silver. When carried in procession, the imposing image of the saint\\u2019s arm raised in blessing could be seen easily by the faithful, even from a distance. The rich combination of materials used for the sleeve of the saint\\u2019s vestment typifies goldsmith\\u2019s work produced in the Meuse Valley, now a part of modern Belgium, and is related to the style of Brother Hugo of Oignies, a celebrated thirteenth-century artist.", "classification": "Metalwork-Silver", "accession_number": "47.101.33", "geographic_location": "Europe,Netherlands", "object_type_material": "Gems,Gilt,Metal,Metalwork,Niellos,Reliquaries,Silver"}

{"date": "ca. 1450 B.C.", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/eg/web-large/DT536.jpg", "title": "Chair of Reniseneb", "medium": "Wood, ebony, ivory", "period": "New Kingdom", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/547687", "dynasty": "Dynasty 18", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "2000\\u20131000 B.C.", "geography": "From Egypt, Upper Egypt, Thebes", "dimensions": "h. 86.2 cm (33 15/16 in)", "credit_line": "Purchase, Patricia R. Lassalle Gift, 1968", "description": "The back of this wooden chair, which belonged to the scribe Reniseneb, is handsomely veneered with ivory and embellished with incised decoration showing the owner seated on a chair of identical form. It is the earliest surviving chair with such a representation, and it is the only non-royal example known. The scene and accompanying text have funerary import and may have been added following Renyseneb's death to make the chair a more suitable funerary object. The high quality of its joinery and the harmony of its proportions testify to the skill of ancient Egyptian carpenters. The mesh seat has been restored following ancient models.", "accession_number": "68.58", "geographic_location": "Africa,Egypt,Thebes,Upper Egypt", "object_type_material": "Bone,Chairs,Ebony,Furniture,Ivory,Seating furniture,Wood"}

column23: {"image": "http://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/ep/web-large/DP155715.jpg", "title": "Jan (1438\\u20131516), First Count of Egmond; Countess of Egmond (Magdalena van Werdenburg, 1464\\u20131538)", "artist": "North Netherlandish Painter (after 1516)", "medium": "Oil on canvas, transferred from wood (.122, the Count); oil on wood (.118, the Countess)", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/436991", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1400\\u20131600", "dimensions": "(.122, the Count): overall, with arched top, 16 3/4 x 10 1/4 in. (41.9 x 24.8 cm)", "credit_line": "The Friedsam Collection, Bequest of Michael Friedsam, 1931", "description": "In 1484, the future count Jan van Egmond married Magdalena van Werdenburg, when he was forty-six and she was twenty years old. Evidently these portraits depict an older couple; rather than celebrating the marriage, they were probably painted upon Jan\\u2019s death. The wizened count wears his highest honor, a collar of the Order of the Golden Fleece, while Magdalena is depicted as a widow, with a black band around her wedding ring. She holds a pink, a symbol of marriage, but unlike the one in a nearby painting (49.7.23), the flower is turned downward, as if to acknowledge Jan\\u2019s passing.", "classification": "Paintings", "accession_number": "32.100.118, 122", "geographic_location": "Europe,Netherlands", "artist_maker_culture": "North Netherlandish Painter", "object_type_material": "Canvas,Oil paint,Paintings,Wood"}

column17: Jacob Marrel (German, Frankenthal 1613/14–1681 Frankfurt am Main)
column19: Four Tulips:  Boter man (Butter Man), Joncker (Nobleman), Grote geplumaceerde (The Great Plumed One), and Voorwint (With the Wind)
column23: {"date": "ca. 1635\\u201345", "image": "https://images.metmuseum.org/CRDImages/dp/web-large/DP805339.jpg", "title": "Four Tulips:  Boter man (Butter Man), Joncker (Nobleman), Grote geplumaceerde (The Great Plumed One), and Voorwint (With the Wind)", "artist": "Jacob Marrel (German, Frankenthal 1613/14\\u20131681 Frankfurt am Main)", "medium": "watercolor on vellum", "source": "http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/337769", "license": "/publicdomain/zero/1.0/", "date_era": "A.D. 1600\\u20131800", "dimensions": "sheet (c.): 13 3/8 x 17 11/16 in. (34 x 44.9 cm)", "credit_line": "Rogers Fund, 1968", "description": "This watercolor on vellum is a remarkable document of a fascinating moment in botanical and economic history, involving a venerated flower and its trade on the stock market. It depicts four different tulip cultivars, each clearly named (Boter man, Joncker, Grote geplumaceerde, Voorwint) and beautifully rendered to record the prized bloom. The sheet comes out of one of several watercolor albums or Tulpenboeken made by the Dutch still-life painter, print- and tulip dealer Jakob Marrel (1613\\u20131681). Married to the widow of the German engraver Matth\\xe4us Merian, Marrel was stepfather and teacher of the well-known botanist-artist Maria Sibylla Merian. In addition to flower paintings, Marrel created at least six tulip books, three of which remain intact. Executed while he worked in Utrecht during the late 1630s and early 1640s, his tulip books coincide with the period when the Dutch developed a true passion for the tulip. Known as Tulipomania, the rage for this flower, especially in its variegated or multistriped form, resulted in wild speculation, ending in 1637 with the crash of the bulb commodity market. Still considered Holland's \"national flower,\" the tulip actually was imported in the 1580s from Turkey, where it had been cultivated by the Ottomans from the beginning of the sixteenth century onward. It was the famous, widely traveled Flemish botanist Carolus Clusius (1526\\u20131609), who, as supervisor of the Leiden Botanical Garden, was instrumental in furthering the introduction of the tulip and other exotic bulbs from West Asia, laying the foundation for Holland's modern-day global bulb industry.", "classification": "Drawings", "accession_number": "68.66", "geographic_location": "Europe,Germany", "artist_maker_culture": "Jacob Marrel", "object_type_material": "Drawings,Parchment,Vellum,Watercolors"}
